nd ethical but failing to live up to their own hype, the leader of the farmers' union will charge today. \par \par \uc2 Peter Kendall, president of the National Farmers' Union, will attack supermarkets, accusing them of pretending to be environmentally friendly but at the same time driving UK farmers out of business by squeezing suppliers' margins. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Mr Kendall's remarks will come as new figures are released showing that farmers in developing countries are at the receiving end of an increasingly better deal from supermarkets. \par \par \uc2 Figures from the Fairtrade Foundation will show that UK sales of Fairtrade-certified products - which guarantee minimum prices for farmers in developing countries - increased 46 per cent to Pounds 290m in 2006. Sales are expected to top Pounds 300m this year. \par \par \uc2 Supermarkets have all been extending their ranges of Fairtrade products as part of their demonstration of ethical credentials. Sainsbury's and Waitrose are due to start selling solely Fairtrade bananas, Tesco is expanding its range of Fairtrade nuts, and Asda and Morrisons plan in-store promotions of fresh Fairtrade produce. \par \par \uc2 Fairtrade-branded products are certified by the Fairtrade Foundation as having been bought at a fair price with an additional "social premium" for local community projects. About 5m people in 58 developing countries, such as Uganda and Nicaragua, benefit from the scheme. \par \par \uc2 "It is an encouraging sign that supermarkets are now falling over each other to paint themselves as the 'greenest' or 'most responsible', but do they really mean it?" Mr Kendall will tell the annual conference of the NFU in Birmingham this morning. "Or is it all about PR - about looking good because of customer expectation while still screwing down the price to the point where three dairy farmers are going out of business every day?" \par \par \uc2 He argues that smaller retailers "are treating their suppliers fairly" but that the big supermarkets are still driving down prices to farmers throughunfair business practices. \par \par \uc2 Farmers are struggling to make a profit from low food prices. "For many farmers and growers, today's prices are not sustainable," Mr Kendall will say. "(Supermarket chains) must understand the farming and growing businesses that comprise that supply base must be profitable . . . That's not just \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ; it is common sense." \par \par \uc2 Justin King, chief executive of J Sainsbury, who has recently returned from the Windward Islands where he has been negotiating extended Fairtrade banana orders, is expected to defend his supermarket's practices in a speech at the conference. David Miliband, \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , food and rural affairs secretary, will also speak. \par \par \uc2 Farmers should also be encouraged to grow crops for fuel, Mr Kendall is expected to say. \par \par \uc2 The government has pledged to increase the UK's biofuels industry, but farmers want binding long-term targets committing Britain to deriving a certain amount of energy from biofuels and biomass, or fuel derived from plants.  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15