ntbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The increasing importance of brands in a competitive global economy, and their growing contribution to the value of the companies that own them, is illustrated in the detailed sector rankings produced by \uc2 Millward Brown\uc2  Optimor for today's special report. \par \par \uc2 As Joanna Seddon, the company's New York-based executive vice-president, points out, a new product or invention may end up copied by competitors very soon after its introduction, but what remains is the value added to the brand. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Some common themes run through many of the sectors: the "rise of the East", for example, is not only fuelling the growth of mainly European luxury brands but is also creating a home for new, indigenous brands to emerge. Across such emerging markets, says Dr Seddon, the brands that are first to become prominent tend to be "infrastructure-related" - that is, energy, banks and telecoms, with other areas such as consumer packaged goods following behind. \par \par \uc2 Other trends include the importance of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 : "If your business has any connection with the automotive sector, positioning yourself ahead on \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues strengthens your brand, and puts you in a good position to conquer new territory and to defend your existing businesses - it reduces your risk," says Dr Seddon. \par \par \uc2 There is also the continuing power of "jumbo brands" such as \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  and Microsoft - neither of which are necessarily beloved as brands but which score highly with consumers for other reasons; the value of brands in a business-to-business context, which can be just as important as in the business-to-consumer space - as illustrated by companies such as \uc2 Goldman Sachs\uc2  and Morgan Stanley; and the maturing of online brands, which need a unique brand and business proposition, says Dr Seddon - "just being online doesn't do it any more". \par \par \uc2 Healthy living and eating trends are also forcing companies to reinvent themselves, says Dr Seddon, and nowhere more so than in fast food. But the rankings in this sector illustrate that powerful brands can cope with change in different ways, including a counter-intuitive approach. "If you've got a really strong brand and you position yourself very clearly, it doesn't matter whether you are following the trend of the day or running counter to it," says Dr Seddon. "Burger King would be an example, it has deliberately positioned itself as the quintessential traditional (i.e. non-healthy) burger." \par \par \uc2 As Peter Walshe, \uc2 Millward Brown\uc2 's global account director, notes, the sector was the fastest growing in terms of brand value last year, with brands that are both distinctive and distinguishing from each other. "When their backs are against the wall, they turn things around," he says. \par \par \uc2 Here are the main points from each of the 14 sectors, with "brand nuggets" and comments from Dr Seddon, Mr Walshe and Paolo Belotti, associate director of \uc2 Millward Brown\uc2  Optimor. \par \par \uc2 Apparel \par \par \uc2 * Brands are extending into home furnishing and other related businesses in search of growth \par \par \uc2 * Ethical trend is leading to partnerships with charities as well as environmentally friendly products \par \par \uc2 * Franchising is used as a means of breaking into smaller, fragmented markets \par \par \uc2 * Efforts to build e-commerce have proved highly profitable for many apparel brands \par \par \uc2 Brand nugget - Zara: is Zara's brand identity strong enough for it to be successful in the home furnishing business? Its current image is affordable, fast-fashion with no distinct look. Are any of these key elements that affect the purchase decision in home furnishing? \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon: "The rankings show that there is a distinct cycle, and that it is very difficult to retain leadership, as there is a strong fashion element. It's the opposite of fast food where everybody is up - here it's all over the place. Gap used to have a very clear retail concept but they were too successful, became ubiquitous and ceased to be differentiated. So they tried to be cool and trendy, which alienated all their 'chinos and white tee-shirt' customers. Now they've tried to get back to their previous position but it's not working. Levi's [in 13th position] are interesting: their brand value is down, which might have been expected - but if you look at their momentum it suggests that after years of trying to turn the brand round they may be making a comeback." \par \par \uc2 Beer \par \par \uc2 * Overall, the category has not shown significant changes in 2006 \par \par \uc2 * There has been growth in regional brands (for example Baltika, Skol) rather than established global brands \par \par \uc2 * China, Latin America and central/eastern Europe are regions with potential for growth \par \par \uc2 * In saturated markets such as the US, consumers are trading up to premium/imported beers \par \par \uc2 * As consumers become more interested in health and fitness there is a preference for light beers \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon: "The story is in the foreign brands and the light brands." Walshe: "Some of the importing of foreign brands is driven by the same luxury story that we have seen in other sectors, with consumers in far eastern markets 'trading up.'" Seddon: "Corona is an interesting story. A run-of-the-mill brand from Mexico has been turned into more of a premium brand in the US, and this incredible brand ritual has been created around it - you have to stick your lime into the top of the bottle. If you can create a ritual like that, it is really the top of branding." \par \par \uc2 Cars \par \par \uc2 * Facing rising health and pension costs, falling demand and intense competition from Asian manufacturers with more fuel-efficient cars and better cost structures, most carmakers are cutting costs, moving manufacturing capacity to cheaper locations, and developing new models \par \par \uc2 * Consumers are shifting from trucks/SUVs to cars and car-based crossover vehicles as a result of higher fuel costs and environmental awareness \par \par \uc2 * China and India are the fastest growing markets and offer significant opportunities for profitability \par \par \uc2 * Further consolidation is expected as carmakers seek to attain additional synergies \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon: "The story here is the strength of Toyota, Honda and the luxury brands, emphasising again the importance of luxury brands for European businesses. Toyota is like the opposite of McDonald's reinventing itself: its kaizen policy of continuous improvement has taken it to a level beyond where anyone can get, both in manufacturing and in consumer insight. It cares about brand far more than the US manufacturers, it gives smaller discounts than any other major manufacturer yet it sells more cars, because it realises it is not about giving it away, but nurturing the brand. Its Prius model illustrates the environmental theme in these rankings and is a hook for the brand right now Toyota is not leading the ranking because it is selling millions of environmentally-friendly cars. Meanwhile, the value of brands such as Ford and Chevrolet has not declined that much, given the companies' financial situations - the brands are stronger than the businesses, if you like." \par \par \uc2 Coffee \par \par \uc2 * Coffee makers are branching out into higher margin items such as ready to drink coffee, coffee pods, etc. \par \par \uc2 * Most brands have extended to premium or flavoured coffee to capitalise on consumers' shift to more sophisticated tastes \par \par \uc2 * There is rising demand for fair trade products \par \par \uc2 * In addition to selling a product, coffee makers are building brand loyalty through web communities \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon: "This is all about the established companies being disrupted comprehensively by Starbucks, which has come at it in a completely different way, and they have been unable to respond." \par \par \uc2 Fast food \par \par \uc2 * After the strong growth of the 1980s and 1990s, there has been a backlash due to the anti-junk, healthy eating movement \par \par \uc2 * The slow food, lounge experience concept is also eating into the fast food business; Starbucks poses a threat to established business models \par \par \uc2 * Fast food companies are reacting by introducing healthy menus and disclosing nutritional values \par \par \uc2 * Some players are taking it one step further by branching out into cafes to revitalise the brands. However, others are reacting to the threat by emphasising their original positioning and product offering. \par \par \uc2 Brand nugget - Starbucks: aggressive expansion in a number of stores as well as product offerings make the Starbucks brand more available and relevant to consumers. \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon: "It is still all-out growth at Starbucks. Certainly in the US, the concept of three places to go - home, work, and Starbucks - that's what it is. It's a destination and a sort of ritual with a strange language and all the rest of it, rather than being about the coffee." Walshe: "The chairman [Howard Schultz, whose leaked memo in February bluntly assessed the drawbacks of the chain's quest for expansion and efficiencies] is right to be concerned that the Starbucks \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and experience is the essence of their brand and that they need to maintain that, as that is what is driving their growth." Seddon: "Overall, what have these brands done? It's not growth in China or India with the same old brand proposition, but reinvention and repositioning in their established European and North American markets. Burger King has reinvented itself but has not kowtowed to the healthy eating trend. McDonald's has done that to some extent, whereas Burger King went back to the basics and said: 'Let's be who we are.'" \par \par \uc2 Financial institutions* \par \par \uc2 * As financial markets become saturated in the developed countries, banks are seeking growth through expansion into emerging markets \par \par \uc2 * Multinational banks are eager to tap into the Chinese banking sector as it fully deregulates the banking industry in December \par \par \uc2 * India's "underbanked" population is being targeted through retail business \par \par \uc2 * The boom in wealthy individuals worldwide has resulted in banks introducing or strengthening wealth management services \par \par \uc2 * For insurers building a single brand has been important \par \par \uc2 * Large insurers such as AIG are rebranding brands acquired to their masterbrand \par \par \uc2 * Importance of brand in developing distribution networks \par \par \uc2 Brand nuggets- HSBC: "world's local bank" successfully builds on its current brand position and taps into different medium with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.yourpointofview.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.yourpointofview.com}}}\uc2  ; UBS: the "You &Us" campaign helped UBS unify its portfolio of brands internally and significantly increased brand awareness among consumers. \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon: "You can see the infrastructure story here, with ICBC and the Bank of China in the Top 10 (and China Construction bank at 16th). Elsewhere, you might expect the brand value of \uc2 Goldman Sachs\uc2  (in 20th place, brand value down 7 per cent) to be growing, but part of the reason why it isn't is because the mix of its business is changing: private equity is not really about the brand whereas investment banking is hugely branded." Walshe: "American Express has done well by not being shy to say: 'We are a premium brand.' The moment they have come back to that, it has paid well for them." \par \par \uc2 *The methodology for calculating brand contribution in B2B sectors has been improved, which explains the slight fluctuation for some brands. \par \par \uc2 Luxurygoods \par \par \uc2 * While still strong in the Far East, demand for European luxury goods in Japan is softening as spending shifts to other categories \par \par \uc2 * There is a trend for brands to extend into the other luxury businesses such as hotel and home \par \par \uc2 * The Armani brand has been extended to Armani Casa and Armani Hotels \par \par \uc2 * Entry into the Indian market will increase as a slew of designer labels announce plans for openings in 2007 - Versace and Fendi are among Italian brands that will tap into the market \par \par \uc2 Brand nuggets - Armani: well executed brand extension and structured architecture allows Armani to lend its brand to new business areas without diluting the brand value; Gucci: expansion of marketing into the online space with podcasts increases brand awareness without losing the luxury image; Moet &Chandon: linking champagne with fashion and glamour increases consumption opportunity and changes champagne's perception as a seasonal product. \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon: "The overarching message is growth, slightly less than in the fast food sector. But whereas growth in fast food was in traditional markets, in luxury goods it is 'Europe in Asia' - defining Asia as Russia eastwards. Hermes and Gucci have done the best job. With Hermes it is their Asian, and particularly their China strategy, that is behind that. Their shop in Shanghai is like a museum or a temple to Hermes, the prices are incredibly high and the idea is to seed into the psyche of the increasingly affluent people in Shanghai that Hermes represents the apogee of luxury. Then the Chinese all go to Hong Kong to buy from the Hermes store there." Walshe: "Most of the top brands in the ranking are multi-product, whereas Rolex is more of a single-product brand, so it has done remarkably well to get into the top 100." Belotti: "It's interesting that you have the co-existence of brands belong to multinationals but also the flourishing of brands that are still pretty much private, such as Armani. One thing that Armani does very well is careful management of its brand portfolio so they can address every segment of the market." \par \par \uc2 Mobile communications \par \par \uc2 * Some major changes of brand values due to: acquisitions, rebranding, financial restatements \par \par \uc2 * Trend for convergence as companies move into non-traditional services by leveraging existing infrastructure \par \par \uc2 * Companies that fail to meet consumer demand in updating network and product range are losing market share \par \par \uc2 * Emerging markets and the US (a laggard in 3G applications) are expected to deliver 60 per cent of forecasted growth over the next five years \par \par \uc2 * Price competition in mature markets is eroding margins \par \par \uc2 * Deregulation in the Chinese market and launch of 3G is likely to encourage competition between the major players \par \par \uc2 * Introduction of number portability will cause higher rate of network changing among consumers \par \par \uc2 Brand nuggets - Orange: has created a strong brand identity associated with films and managed to build consumer loyalty with incentives such as free movie tickets on Wednesdays; Movistar: its "Lend Me 2" service is an industry first and may kick start a new service throughout the industry \par \par \uc2 Comment - Belotti: "This is the only category where brand value overall has fallen, but that is the least you would expect in a sector where there is so much price pressure. With T-Mobile, you have to wonder how much of the decline in brand value is due to its whole message, which in the advertising is all about 'we are the cheapest'. Vodafone, meanwhile, is another great story about brand resilience, the strength of the brand has limited the damage on the financial front - that 12 per cent decline is mainly due to the huge writedown in the value of the Mannesmann acquisition." Seddon: "Only two brand contributions in this category score above two, China Mobile and Verizon. China Mobile has built a very strong brand very deliberately. Verizon has really succeeded at creating a brand around a new name, rather than just sticking all the old company names together as many telecoms do after mergers. It felt it had to get away from the old utility image." \par \par \uc2 Motor fuel \par \par \uc2 * BP and Shell lead the trend in repositioning their brands as global energy companies that confront the conflict between energy and environmental needs, and take actions beyond what is expected of an oil company \par \par \uc2 * BRIC (Brazil, Russia, India and China) energy companies seem to have strong brands but this is largely due to their historical status as monopolies \par \par \uc2 * Supermarket petrol retailers are gaining market share as customers take advantage of loyalty cards and combine various errands in one trip \par \par \uc2 * Recent high crude oil prices are reflected in retail prices, but only marginally inform consumers' purchase behaviour \par \par \uc2 Brand nuggets - BP: successful repositioning of the brand as innovative, progressive and environmentally responsible has not only improved brand perception but has also enabled additional retail opportunities ("beyond petroleum"); Shell: rebranding improved perception of brand as environmentally friendly; also, sales growth in rebranded stations \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon: "The top two brands happen to be the ones that have taken more of an environmental/\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  position. BP, despite all the negative publicity, is still in first place, showing the strength of its brand. Shell's brand value has grown more, but it did not have the same issues to contend with. Meanwhile the two new brands in the ranking illustrate how, in emerging markets, the first brands to become prominent are 'infrastructure-related' - oil, banks or telcos. With Petrochina the value is probably more in the size of the business than the excellence of the brand. Lukoil is a stage further ahead and is beginning to think about brand. It's expanding quite aggressively outside Russia - there's even some gas stations in New Jersey." \par \par \uc2 Personal care \par \par \uc2 * Dramatic increases in brand value for several brands in the category, mainly driven by increase of disposable income in fast growing countries \par \par \uc2 * Companies have increased marketing spend as well as frequency of new products as strategies to boost performance and compete for market share \par \par \uc2 * Growth segments have included premium products, anti-ageing products and products based on natural/organic ingredients. \par \par \uc2 Brand nugget - Dove: the "real beauty" campaign continues to generate interests and discussions, especially the viral campaign which can be seen on YouTube.com \par \par \uc2 Comment - Belotti: "The brand growth champions, \uc2 Shiseido\uc2  and Olay, are benefiting for their positioning, which is more of a premium, 'trading up' concept. They are doing particularly well in Asia, which is consistent with the overall trend on luxury brands. Gillette is also interesting: although it is in the middle of a reorganisation following the takeover by Procter &Gamble, and has not launched any new 'killer' products in the recent past, its brand value has still grown." Walshe: "The Colgate story is very interesting because it is absolutely clear what the brand stands for, and it is driven by very clear, consistent communications which always underline the brand." Seddon: "Toothpaste as a whole has done well at brand extension - where once there was just toothpaste there are now 57 varieties. Overall the three big brands, Gillette, L'Oreal and Colgate are all innovation stories, along with brand consistency and excellence in marketing. Avon, in fourth place, is different, but its direct sales strategy is perfect for the Chinese market." \par \par \uc2 Retailing \par \par \uc2 * Established brands face competitors brandishing cut-rate prices, although some have succeeded in avoiding a price war by introducing premium own-brand products \par \par \uc2 * Supermarket brands are extending their offerings beyond grocery \par \par \uc2 * As growth in club membership approaches its limits, pressure is on warehouse clubs to generate larger baskets and more frequent trips to sustain the rapid growth of the industry's early years \par \par \uc2 * The new competition ground is China, where most western chains are seeking to grab a share of the seventh largest consumer market \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon: " \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  is the jumbo brand - it has a brand but that is a very small proportion of its value. It is No. 1 because it is so big." Belotti: "If you look at Asda's growth against that of \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2 , it shows the wisdom of not changing the brand name [after Asda was taken over by the US group]. Asda is such a powerful and traditional brand in the UK." Walshe: " \uc2 Marks and Spencer\uc2  is the highest growth brand in the entire Top 100. The brand was sleeping and it was waiting to get the products right, and it all came together at the same time. The momentum suggests it has not finished yet. But there is a wider story here about the different ways these brands are growing - with the hard discounters such as Aldi and Costco on the one side and the more upmarket brands such as M&S on the other." Seddon: "In the US there is a huge battle between \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  with its everyday low prices and Target, where prices are slightly higher but the store designs and image are cooler. There is a lot of debate about which is the right business model but what this says is that both work." \par \par \uc2 Soft drinks \par \par \uc2 * The sector is affected by the campaigns against junk food. \par \par \uc2 * The UK has imposed a total ban on junk food advertising around children's programming, on all children's channels and around all programmes that have "particular appeal" to under 16-year-olds \par \par \uc2 * In the US, the world's three largest soft drinks companies have agreed to ban most soda sales in public schools and distribute only lower-calorie and nutritious beverages to tackle childhood obesity \par \par \uc2 * Increase in price of raw materials - aluminium, high-fructose corn syrup and oranges - could raise the industry's costs by $1bn in 2007 \par \par \uc2 * Areas ripe for growth in North America are health and wellness, natural and organic products, and premium products \par \par \uc2 Comment - Walshe: "The average growth in brand value is only 4 per cent, compared with 10-10.5 per cent for the sectors as a whole, and part of the reason for this is health concerns." Seddon: "If you compare soft drinks with what has happened in fast food, we haven't yet seen such successful reinvention and repositioning. With food, you can experiment with less risk and cost." \par \par \uc2 Technology \par \par \uc2 Hardware: \par \par \uc2 * Race to occupy high value segments \par \par \uc2 * Tide of commoditisation in consumer electronics compels companies to consistently innovate \par \par \uc2 * Commoditisation of the desktop PC (Dell and HP) \par \par \uc2 * Apple has differentiated itself through innovation, Sony however has lost its way * Korean and Chinese companies have invested in brand building to enter high-end segments (Samsung) \par \par \uc2 * Intel faces threat from AMD, but will the Intel brand act as an insurance policy against loss of market share? \par \par \uc2 Software: \par \par \uc2 * B2B convergence: SAP and Oracle are expanding into each other's core segments, to provide a one-stop shop for B2B clients; IBM is losing out to SAP and Oracle, which are well positioned to offer value-added services to their customers \par \par \uc2 * B2C convergence: The Microsoft brand is struggling to acquire a leading position in home entertainment; Adobe is benefiting from media disintermediation \par \par \uc2 Mobile handsets: \par \par \uc2 * Emerging markets are driving growth: rapid growth in south-east Asia, India, Middle East, Africa; increased demand for low margin, low-end phones damage gross margins; potential for further mobile phone penetration in China \par \par \uc2 * Slowing growth in mature markets: growth of higher margin, high-end handsets to offset slowing growth \par \par \uc2 * Mobile phones are acquiring extra functionality: mobile handsets threaten the demand for other portable devices (mp3 players, palmtop PCs, digital cameras) \par \par \uc2 Brand nuggets:Motorola with D&G, and LG with Prada, have co-designed mobile handsets; Intel is to provide microprocessors for new Apple PCs, posing branding questions for both companies. Apple will be unlikely to want to compromise its PC design by including the Intel logo. \par \par \uc2 Comment - Belotti: "The general point about 'Just being online doesn't do it' is illustrated by Google and Yahoo - the same starting point and similar kind of development into the online landscape, but very different results. Apple, meanwhile, continues the trend we saw last year, showing that it is so much more than just a hardware manufacturer." \par \par \uc2 Water \par \par \uc2 * Bottled water is a commoditised sector with limited growth and fierce competition, which explains a decline in brand contribution across the category \par \par \uc2 * Growth is observed in emerging markets, especially China \par \par \uc2 * Still water represents the main category growth driver as health awareness rises in consumers \par \par \uc2 * Continuous innovation and aggressive promotion will be paramount to stay afloat \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon: "This is a much more fragmented market than soft drinks, with so many little brands. Nestle, for example, owns a collection of water brands but has just left them as individual regional brands. No company has yet succeeded at the challenge of creating a global water brand.  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 55633993\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adj