rin0\lin0 \uc2 Surveys GMI1\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PG\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 Page 4\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2007 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The increasing importance of brands in a competitive global economy, and their growing contribution to the value of the companies that own them, is illustrated in the detailed sector rankings produced by Millward Brown Optimor for today's special report. \par \par \uc2 As Joanna Seddon, the company's New York-based executive vice-president, points out, a new product or invention may be copied by competitors very soon after its introduction, but what remains is the value added to the brand. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Some common themes run through many of the sectors: the "rise of the East", for example, is not only fuelling the growth of mainly European luxury brands but is also creating a place for new, indigenous brands to emerge. \par \par \uc2 Across such emerging markets, says Ms Seddon, the brands that are first to emerge tend to be "infrastructure-related" - that is, energy, banks and telecoms, with other areas such as consumer packaged goods following behind. \par \par \uc2 Other trends include the importance of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . "If your business has any connection with the automotive sector, positioning yourself ahead on \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues strengthens your brand, and puts you in a good position to conquer new territory and to defend your existing businesses. It reduces your risk," says Ms Seddon. \par \par \uc2 There is also the continuing power of "jumbo brands" such as Wal-Mart and Microsoft. Neither of them is necessarily beloved as a brand but each scores highly for other reasons. \par \par \uc2 Then there is the value of brands in a business-to-business context, which can be just as important as in the business-to-consumer space.This point is illustrated by companies such as Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley. Another feature is the maturing of online brands, which need a unique brand and business proposition, says Ms Seddon: "Just being online doesn't do it any more." \par \par \uc2 Healthy living and eating trends are also forcing companies to reinvent themselves, says Ms Seddon, and nowhere more so than in fast food. But the rankings in this sector illustrate that powerful brands can cope with change in different ways, including a counter-intuitive approach. \par \par \uc2 "If you've got a really strong brand and you position yourself very clearly, it doesn't matter whether you are following the trend of the day or running counter to it," says Ms Seddon. "Burger King is an example: it has deliberately positioned itself as the quintessential traditional (i.e. non-healthy) burger." \par \par \uc2 As Peter Walshe, Millward Brown's global account director, notes, the sector was the fastest growing in terms of brand value last year, with brands that are both distinctive and distinguishing from each other. "When their backs are against the wall, they turn things round," he says. \par \par \uc2 Here are the main points from each of the 14 sectors, with comments from Ms Seddon, Mr Walshe and Paolo Belotti, MBO's associate director. Longer versions of several of the tables - the top 15 for Apparel, Beer, Cars and Retail, top 20 for Technology and Personal Care and top 25 for Financial Services - are published on FT.com at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.ft.com/globalbrands2007"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.ft.com/globalbrands2007}}}\uc2  , along with expanded comments. \par \par \uc2 Apparel \par \par \uc2 * Brands are extending into home furnishing and other related businesses in search of growth \par \par \uc2 * The ethical trend is leading to partnerships with charities as well as environmentally-friendly products \par \par \uc2 * Franchising is used as a means of breaking into smaller, fragmented markets \par \par \uc2 * Efforts to build e-commerce have proved highly profitable for many apparel brands \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon:"This shows that there is a distinct cycle, and that it is very difficult to retain leadership, as there is a strong fashion element. It's the opposite of fast food, where everybody is up - here it's all over the place. \par \par \uc2 Gap used to have a very clear retail concept, but they were too successful, became ubiquitous and ceased to be differentiated. So they tried to be cool and trendy, which alienated all their 'chinos and white T-shirt' customers. Now they've tried to get back to their previous position but it's not working." \par \par \uc2 Beer \par \par \uc2 * There has been growth in regional brands (for example Baltika, Skol) rather than established global brands \par \par \uc2 * China, Latin America and central/eastern Europe are regions with potential for growth \par \par \uc2 * In saturated markets such as the US, consumers are trading up to premium/imported beers \par \par \uc2 * As consumers become more interested in health and fitness, they prefer light beers \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon:"The story is in the foreign brands and the light brands." Walshe:"Some of the importing of foreign brands is driven by the same luxury story that we have seen in other sectors, with consumers in East Asian markets 'trading up'." \par \par \uc2 Cars \par \par \uc2 * Facing rising health and pension costs, falling demand and intense competition from Asian manufacturers with more fuel-efficient cars and better cost structures, most carmakers are cutting costs, moving manufacturing to cheaper locations, and developing new models \par \par \uc2 * Consumers are shifting from trucks/SUVs to cars and car-based crossover vehicles as a result of higher fuel costs and environmental awareness \par \par \uc2 * China and India are the fastest growing markets and offer significant opportunities for profitability \par \par \uc2 * Further consolidation is expected, as carmakers seek to attain additional synergies \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon:"The story here is the strength of Toyota, Honda and the luxury brands, emphasising again the importance of luxury brands for European businesses. Toyota is like the opposite of McDonald's reinventing itself: its kaizen policy of continuous improvement has taken it to a level beyond where anyone can get, both in manufacturing and in consumer insight. Meanwhile, the value of brands such as Ford and Chevrolet has not declined that much, given the companies' financial situations - the brands are stronger than the businesses, if you like." \par \par \uc2 Coffee \par \par \uc2 * Coffee companies are branching out into higher margin items such as ready-to-drink coffee, coffee pods, and so on. \par \par \uc2 * Most brands have extended to premium or flavoured coffee to capitalise on consumers' shift to more sophisticated tastes \par \par \uc2 * There is rising demand for fairtrade products \par \par \uc2 * As well as selling a product, coffee makers are building brand loyalty through the web \par \par \uc2 Fast Food \par \par \uc2 * After the strong growth of the 1980s and 1990s, there has been a backlash due to the anti-junk, healthy eating movement \par \par \uc2 * The slow food, lounge experience concept is also eating into the fast food business; Starbucks poses a threat to established business models \par \par \uc2 * Fast food companies are reacting by introducing healthy menus and disclosing nutritional values \par \par \uc2 * Some companies are taking it one step further by branching out into cafes to revitalise the brands. However, others are reacting to the threat by emphasising their original positioning and product offering. \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon: "It is still all-out growth at Starbucks. It's a destination and a sort of ritual with a strange language and all the rest of it, rather than being about the coffee." \par \par \uc2 Walshe:The Starbucks chairman (Howard Schultz, whose leaked memo in February bluntly assessed the drawbacks of the chain's quest for expansion and efficiencies) is right to be concerned that the Starbucks \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and experience is the essence of the brand and that the company needs to maintain that, as that is what is driving growth."Seddon:"Overall, what have these brands done? It's not growth in China or India with the same old brand proposition, but reinvention and repositioning in their established European and North American markets. Burger King has reinvented itself but has not kowtowed to the healthy eating trend. McDonald's has done that to some extent, whereas Burger King went back to the basics and said: 'Let's be who we are.'" \par \par \uc2 Financial institutions* \par \par \uc2 * As financial markets become saturated in the developed countries, banks are seeking growth through expansion into emerging markets \par \par \uc2 * Multinational banks are eager to tap into the Chinese banking sector, as it fully deregulates the banking industry in December \par \par \uc2 * For insurers, building a single brand has been important \par \par \uc2 * Large insurers such as Aviva, Allianz and AIG are rebranding brands acquired to their masterbrand \par \par \uc2 * Importance of brand in developing distribution networks \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon:"You can see the infrastructure story here, with ICBC and the Bank of China in the Top 10 (and China Construction bank at 16th). Elsewhere, you might expect the brand value of Goldman Sachs (in 20th place, brand value down 7 per cent) to be growing, but part of the reason why it isn't is because the mix of its business is changing: private equity is not really about the brand, whereas investment banking is hugely branded."Walshe:"American Express has done well by not being shy to say: 'We are a premium brand'. The moment they came back to that, it paid well for them." \par \par \uc2 *The methodology for calculating brand contribution in B2B sectors has been improved, which explains the slight fluctuation for some brands. \par \par \uc2 Luxury \par \par \uc2 * While still strong in East Asia, demand for European luxury goods in Japan is softening, as spending shifts to other categories \par \par \uc2 * There is a trend for brands to extend into the other luxury businesses, such as hotel and home \par \par \uc2 * The Armani brand has been extended to Armani Casa and Armani Hotels \par \par \uc2 * Entry into the Indian market \par \par \uc2 will increase, as a slew of designer labels announce plans for openings in 2007. Versace and Fendi are among Italian brands that will tap into the market \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon: "The overarching message is growth, but at a slightly lower rate than in the fast food sector. But whereas growth in fast food was in traditional markets, in luxury goods it is 'Europe in Asia' - defining Asia as Russia eastwards. Hermes and Gucci have done the best job with this." Walshe: "Most of the top brands in the ranking are multi-product, whereas Rolex is more of a single-product brand, so it has done remarkably well to get into the top 100." Belotti: "It's interesting that you have the co-existence of brands belonging to multinationals but also the flourishing of brands that are still pretty much private, such as Armani." \par \par \uc2 Mobile Networks \par \par \uc2 * Some big changes of brand values due to: acquisitions, rebranding, financial restatements \par \par \uc2 * Trend for convergence, as companies move into non-traditional services by leveraging existing infrastructure \par \par \uc2 * Companies that fail to meet consumer demand in updating network and product range are losing market share \par \par \uc2 * Emerging markets and the US (a laggard in 3G applications) are expected to deliver 60 per cent of forecasted growth over the next five years \par \par \uc2 Comment - Belotti: "This is the only category where brand value overall has fallen, but that is the least you would expect in a sector where there is so much price pressure. With T-Mobile, you have to wonder how much of the decline in brand value is due to its whole message, which in the advertising is all about 'we are the cheapest'. Vodafone, meanwhile, is another great story about brand resilience, the strength of the brand has limited the damage on the financial front." Seddon: "Only two brand contributions in this category score above two, China Mobile and Verizon. China Mobile has built a strong brand very deliberately. Verizon has succeeded at creating a brand around a new name. It felt it had to get away from the old utility image (of AT&T)." \par \par \uc2 Motor Fuel \par \par \uc2 * BP and Shell lead the trend in repositioning their brands as global energy companies that confront the conflict between energy and environmental needs, and take actions beyond what is expected of an oil company \par \par \uc2 * Bric (Brazil, Russia, India and China) energy companies seem to have strong brands, but this is largely due to their historical status as monopolies \par \par \uc2 * Supermarket petrol retailers are gaining market share, as customers take advantage of loyalty cards and combine various errands in one trip \par \par \uc2 * Recent high crude oil prices are reflected in retail prices, but only marginally inform consumers' purchase behaviour \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon: "The top two brands happen to be the ones that have taken more of an environmental/\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  position. BP, despite all the negative publicity, is still in first place, showing the strength of its brand. Shell's brand value has grown more, but it did not have the same issues to contend with. Meanwhile, the two new brands in the ranking, Petrochina and Lukoil, illustrate how, in emerging markets, the first brands to become prominent are 'infrastructure-related' - oil, banks or telcos. Lukoil is beginning to think about brand. It's expanding quite aggressively outside Russia - there's even some Lukoil gas stations in New Jersey." \par \par \uc2 Personal Care \par \par \uc2 * Large increases in brand value for several brands in the category, mainly driven by rises in disposable income in fast growing countries \par \par \uc2 * Companies have increased marketing spend and the frequency of new products as strategies to boost performance and compete for market share \par \par \uc2 * Growth segments have included premium lines, anti-ageing products and those based on natural/organic ingredients. \par \par \uc2 Comment - Belotti: "The brand growth champions, Shiseido and Olay, are benefiting from their positioning, which is more of a premium, 'trading up' concept. They are doing particularly well in Asia. \par \par \uc2 "Gillette is also interesting: although it is in the middle of a reorganisation following the takeover by Procter &Gamble, and has not launched any 'killer' products in the recent past, its brand value has still grown." Walshe: "The Colgate story is interesting, because it is absolutely clear what the brand stands for, and it is driven by very clear, consistent communications which always underline the brand." \par \par \uc2 Retailing \par \par \uc2 * Established brands face competitors with cut-rate prices, although some have succeeded in avoiding a price war by introducing premium own-brand products \par \par \uc2 * Supermarket brands are extending beyond grocery \par \par \uc2 * As growth in club membership approaches its limits, pressureis on warehouse clubs to generate larger baskets and more frequent trips to sustain the growth of the industry's early years \par \par \uc2 * The new competition ground is China, where most western chains are seeking to grab a share of the seventh largest consumer market \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon: "Wal-Mart is the jumbo brand - it has a brand but that is a very small proportion of its value. It is No. 1 because it is so big." Walshe: "Marks and Spencer is the highest growth \par \par \uc2 brand in the entire Top 100. The brand was sleeping and it was waiting to get the products right, and it all came together at the same time. The momentum suggests it has not finished yet. \par \par \uc2 "But there is a wider story here about the different ways these brands are growing - with the hard discounters such as Aldi and Costco on the one side and the more upmarket brands such as M&S on the other." \par \par \uc2 Seddon: "In the US, there is a huge battle between Wal-Mart with its everyday low prices and Target, where prices are slightly higher but the store designs and image are cooler. There is a lot of debate about which is the right model - but what this says is that both work." \par \par \uc2 Soft Drinks \par \par \uc2 * The sector is affected by the campaigns against junk food and related advertising. \par \par \uc2 * An increase in the price of raw materials could raise the industry's costs by Dollars 1bn in 2007 \par \par \uc2 * Areas ripe for growth in North America are "health and wellness", natural and organic products, and premium products \par \par \uc2 Comment - Walshe:"The average growth in brand value is only 4 per cent, compared with 10-10.5 per cent for the sectors as a whole, and part of the reason for this is health concerns." \par \par \uc2 Seddon: "If you compare soft drinks with fast food, we haven't yet seen such successful reinvention and repositioning in response to health trends. With food, you can experiment with less risk and cost" \par \par \uc2 Technology \par \par \uc2 Hardware: \par \par \uc2 * There is a race to occupy high value segments \par \par \uc2 * A tide of commoditisation in consumer electronics compels companies consistently to innovate \par \par \uc2 * The desktop PC is being commoditised \par \par \uc2 Software: \par \par \uc2 * B2B convergence: SAP and Oracle are expanding into each other's core segments, to provide a one-stop shop for B2B clients; IBM is losing out to SAP and Oracle, which are well positioned to offer value-added services to their customers \par \par \uc2 * B2C convergence: The Microsoft brand is struggling to acquire a leading position in home entertainment; Adobe is benefiting from media disintermediation \par \par \uc2 Mobile Handsets: \par \par \uc2 * Emerging markets are driving growth. South-east Asia, India, the Middle East and Africa are seeing rapid expansion. There is also potential for further mobile phone penetration in China \par \par \uc2 * Growth is slowing in mature markets, but this is offset by increased uptake of higher margin, high-end handsets \par \par \uc2 Comment - Belotti: "The general point about 'Just being online doesn't do it' is illustrated by Google and Yahoo - the same starting point and similar kind of development into the online landscape, but very different results. Apple, meanwhile, continues the trend we saw last year, showing that it is so much more than just a hardware manufacturer." \par \par \uc2 Water \par \par \uc2 * Bottled water is a commoditised sector with limited growth and fierce competition, which explains a decline in brand contribution across the category \par \par \uc2 * Still water represents the main category growth driver, as health awareness rises in consumers \par \par \uc2 Comment - Seddon: "This is a much more fragmented market than soft drinks, with so many little brands. Nestle, for example, owns a collection of water brands, but has just left them as individual regional brands. No company has yet succeeded at the challenge of creating a global water brand."  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspa