ntbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Siemens is desperately trying to clean up its image, tarnished by bribery and corruption scandals. Yet the supervisory board of the German engineering conglomerate now risks adding its own stains to the company's reputation, rather than improving it. Reports that some directors are seeking to wipe the slate clean by ousting Klaus Kleinfeld as chief executive, only days after the company's chairman, Heinrich von Pierer, stepped down, smack of an attempted boardroom coup rather than good governance. \par \par \uc2 The board is due to decide on Mr Kleinfeld's future on Wednesday. Of course, the chief executive is not everybody's cup of tea. He is impetuous and self-confident. But his record is good, as second-quarter results are expected to show tomorrow. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Suggestions that the board was considering replacing him sent Siemens shares sliding after their recent recovery. For, whatever his traits, investors have been impressed by Mr Kleinfeld's approach. He also has the advantage of not being embroiled in the scandals now bedevilling the company, since he was neither on the management board nor on the supervisory board when they allegedly took place. \par \par \uc2 Ironically, this is not the case of Gerhard Cromme, the ThyssenKrupp chairman and architect of Germany's corporate governance code, who is now about to step into Mr von Pierer's shoes as Siemens' chairman. Mr Cromme has long been a Siemens director and was the head - and still is - of the audit committee when the scandals allegedly occurred. \par \par \uc2 Given his reputation as a champion of corporate governance, it was probably an obvious choice to put Mr Cromme in the supervisory board chair until January. Yet Mr Cromme has not shown himself to be particularly shareholder friendly. After all, at ThyssenKrupp he supported the decision to increase the board representation of the Krupp foundation - a move regarded by many as an anti-takeover poison pill. \par \par \uc2 More worrying are indications that Mr Cromme wants to remain as chairman of Siemens longer. If so, he would appear to be treating the appointment as a career move, since the Siemens chairmanship is the plum job in German industry. \par \par \uc2 Were he to stay on, a key question is how he would handle an increasingly powerful chief executive such as Mr Kleinfeld. Would he support him, or would he block him? \par \par \uc2 Some directors are pressing for total change at the top. Yet total change would imply not only a new chief executive but a true outsider, not a long serving board member such as Mr Cromme, to come in as chairman as early as possible. \par \par \uc2 It would also seem fitting that the new chairman is closely involved in any decision over the future of Mr Kleinfeld, who continues to have the support of some board members and the markets. The last thing Siemens needs is old-style power games played out in its divided boardroom. \par \par \uc2 Locusts in Switzerland \par \par \uc2 The Swiss regularly praise their financial markets as paragons of transparency thanks to the preponderance of big, multinational groups that encourage best practice. But recent events have shown the rules are as hollow as Emmental cheese, as three big quoted companies have seen large stakes change hands without public disclosure. In Converium, Implenia and Sulzer, stakes of up to 32 per cent have been amassed covertly, in spite of laws requiring disclosure at regular thresholds after 5 per cent. \par \par \uc2 Converium, the mid-sized reinsurer, came into play after Swiss raider Martin Ebner sold his holding to Scor. Implenia, Switzerland's biggest builder, then learned a UK hedge fund controlled almost 25 per cent of its capital. Most recently, Sulzer, one of Switzerland's most famous engineering names, discovered that 32 per cent of its stock was held by an Austro-Russian investment vehicle. \par \par \uc2 The Sulzer story is instructive. Its shares have risen sharply for months on speculation the Austrians were about to pounce. Their Victory investment vehicle had already scored with \uc2 Unaxis\uc2 , the technology group renamed OC Oerlikon, and \uc2 Saurer\uc2 , a maker of textile machinery. \par \par \uc2 Initially, the Swiss were slow to react, partly because \uc2 Unaxis\uc2  and \uc2 Saurer\uc2  were largely unloved companies with patchy histories and because of a cultural tendency to be patronising about anything Austrian. \par \par \uc2 But the Austrians' easy funding and use of so-called cash settlement options - which do not have to be declared under Swiss rules - have now made the raiders deeply unpopular - and deeply feared. \par \par \uc2 Switzerland's regulator plans urgent changes to force cash settlement options into the open. Parliament is debating similar legislation, along with lowering the disclosure threshold to 3 per cent. \par \par \uc2 But such changes have come too late for Sulzer, whose chairman warns such loopholes raise questions about Switzerland as a financial centre. haig.simonian@ft.com \par \par \uc2 Lessons for Newmont \par \par \uc2 Large mining companies do not usually deserve sympathy when accused of polluting the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . When the company is Newmont, the world's largest gold miner, and it is accused of dumping thousands of tonnes of tailings every day into a pristine bay in Indonesia and local people are falling sick, cheering the prosecution seems natural. \par \par \uc2 But for once the evidence stacks up the other way, and yesterday's acquittal of Newmont's local subsidiary and its chief executive should be applauded. \par \par \uc2 The water in Buyat Bay, on the northern tip of Sulawesi island, was tested 12 times after the allegations were made in 2004. The only "polluted" sampling was conducted by the Indonesian police. That was credibly exposed as unreliable during the trial. None of the people who initially accused Newmont of endangering human health corroborated their allegations. None of the mud that local \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  groups threw at Newmont stuck. \par \par \uc2 The case was not a complete victory for Newmont, however. Last year it defeated a $135m civil suit brought by the government, but only by agreeing to pay $30m over 10 years to establish a foundation to oversee community development near the mine. Its costs in fighting the case are thought to be in the same ballpark. \par \par \uc2 Some analysts say that if a fraction of this money had been invested in more extensive \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  projects before 2004 and if Newmont had not dismissed the accusations for the first few weeks, it would not have endured more than two years of legal hell. \par \par \uc2 Sobering lessons for any manager. john.aglionby@ft.com  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\ro