palpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Winner: KPMG LLPRunners-up: Impact Development Training Group, Chiswick Park Enjoy WorkSupported by: AccountAbility \par \par \uc2 Describing the music business, Hunter S. Thompson wrote of a "cruel and shallow money trench, a long plastic hallway where thieves and pimps run free, and good men die like dogs". \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Dispelling the image conveyed by this quote - which is cited on the website of Chiswick Park, a runner-up in the corporate responsibility category of the Best Workplaces awards - is what companies, as they embrace corporate responsibility, believe will help them attract, retain and motivate the best employees. \par \par \uc2 While today, few self-respecting companies are without corporate responsibility programmes and mission statements, many have struggled to establish a tangible business case for the investment in these programmes. However, in recent years, it has become clear that staff motivation is a powerful bottom-line benefit of corporate responsibility. \par \par \uc2 "The employee audience has really become a major driver of this," says Robert Davies, chief executive of the International Business Leaders Forum, which works with corporations to promote responsible business practices. \par \par \uc2 Evidence is emerging that staff are concerned about the ethical behaviour of the companies for whom they work. Some 86 per cent of British workers believe it is important that their employer should be responsible to society and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , according to a report published in November by Ipsos MORI, the research company. \par \par \uc2 Another manifestation of this is the proliferation of business school courses whose content incorporates corporate responsibility. The most recent ranking for the biennial Beyond Grey Pinstripes awards - which track MBA programmes incorporate social and environmental issues - found that, in participating schools, the number requiring students to take one or more courses in ethics, \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , sustainability or business and society rose to 54 per cent - up from and 34 per cent in 2001. \par \par \uc2 "Student demand for corporate responsibility teaching is increasing, but not just for full-time students straight out of college," says Alyson Warhurst, a professor at Warwick Business School. "Increasingly we are seeing business executives taking time out to add corporate responsibility skills to their portfolios, and requesting specialist corporate responsibility modules." \par \par \uc2 Particularly in the UK, the push by retailers to meet the demands of a growing number of ethical shoppers has raised the profile of the ethical practices of businesses. Marks and Spencer, for example, is inviting shoppers to "look behind the label" at the sustainability of its products, as well as its labour, fair trade and animal welfare practices. \par \par \uc2 As global warming has taken centre stage, companies have implemented carbon reduction programmes. Tesco has embarked on an ambitious labelling initiative that will eventually let shoppers compare all its products on their carbon emissions levels. And, of course, shoppers are also employees who want to see similar practices in action not only in the supermarket aisle but also in the workplace. \par \par \uc2 "People are in search of meaning at work," says Linda Holbeche, director of leadership and consultancy at the Work Foundation. "And people are talking about the way in which organisations walk the talk on things like CSR." \par \par \uc2 The activities of leading business figures such as Bill Gates - whose foundation is tackling global health problems such as the spread of HIV/Aids - have also increased the desire on the part of workers to see their employers take action on some of the world's social and health problems. \par \par \uc2 Companies are responding. Impact Development Training Group, a runner up in the Best Workplaces awards corporate responsibility category, is involved in establishing a global project team to develop the capacity of those leading the fight against HIV/Aids in Zambia. \par \par \uc2 The ability for staff to participate in community initiatives is important, too. KPMG, winner in this year's corporate responsibility category, offers staff the chance to volunteer. In 2006, 31 per cent of its workforce volunteered, contributing 32,000 hours to community projects. \par \par \uc2 The company has recognised that such commitments are what help it attract and retain top talent, from both executives and graduates. In 2006, it established a board-level CSR team. \par \par \uc2 "If you want to be a great place to work, then it is not just about base salary and benefits," says Mike Kelly, UK head of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  at KPMG. "People expect leading companies to provide leading remuneration packages and expect the best in training and development, but increasingly they expect to work in an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  where they can contribute to the community."  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\p