par\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Are women inherently more altruistic than men? \par \par \uc2 The question has long exercised equal rights campaigners, who argue that the idea is merely an excuse for low pay in the caring professions. Meanwhile, academics have wondered how western societies will cope with the decline in women's traditional willingness to look after others. But today's survey of graduate employment choices seems to suggest that female altruism is alive and well in the jobs market. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Among the top ten employers picked by female students, only two are private sector companies: L'Oreal, the international cosmetics brand, and PwC, the corporate services group. Otherwise, the female ranking is dominated by public and voluntary sector employers, indicating that women students like the idea of making a difference to public life - a finding described as "worrying" by private sector recruitment professionals. \par \par \uc2 Both sexes put MI5 and the BBC in their top three choices. But there the similarities end. Male students favour Microsoft, Google, Sony and Rolls-Royce - companies with the highest consumer name recognition in the traditional male-dominated sectors of technology and engineering. They are also attracted to the high pressure and high rewards on offer at Goldman Sachs, the investment bank. \par \par \uc2 In stark contrast, the National Health Service, the police, Oxfam, the \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  Agency, and Teach First, a scheme to give top graduates experience of teaching in a state school, all make it into women students' top 10 ranking. \par \par \uc2 The dramatically different female choices push the NHS and L'Oreal into the overall top ten employers for 2007, in spite of a relative lack of enthusiasm from the men. And with nearly 19 per cent of females in the survey preferring the BBC as their ideal employer, compared to 11.5 per cent of the male students, the corporation comes out as the most attractive employer for graduates overall. According to Carl Gilleard, chief executive of the Association of Graduate Recruiters (AGR), an organisation with over 700 public and private sector members, this tendency for women to favour public or voluntary sector employers is long-standing but still "alarming". \par \par \uc2 "Altruism has always had an impact on career choices, but it may be becoming more marked, and it is something that employers are becoming increasingly concerned about," he says. "It is quite alarming because employers know that 55 per cent of students on first degree courses are female, so it affects recruitment even at the investment banks and accountancy firms if the women are heavily motivated to apply elsewhere." Marketing strategies and techniques are being adapted, he says, to try and attract more female applicants to private sector businesses. Meanwhile, other more "touchy-feely" elements of a company's profile are being emphasised. \par \par \uc2 "There is a sense that graduates are becoming a bit more discerning about the type of employer they favour. For example, a good record on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  or a good environmental record will sometimes sway a candidate." \par \par \uc2 The biggest difficulty is for companies in science, technology, engineering and manufacturing, who are faced with an overwhelmingly male pool of students from which to recruit. Mr Gilleard says it is quite a challenge for them to try and fight for the attention even of those few women on science degree courses if those individuals would instinctively prefer to use their skills working for a not-for-profit organisation. \par \par \uc2 He calls for more efforts from employers working with schools to influence girls' GCSE and A-level choices. "They need to do a really bold sell on these science careers," he says. \par \par \uc2 There may be lessons from those companies who have been successful in attracting female graduates. \par \par \uc2 Of the two private companies favoured by the female students, L'Oreal has a ubiquitous brand and a catchy post-feminist slogan - "Because you're worth it" - which helps enormously with the company's recruitment across Europe. But it also makes efforts to promote itself as an excellent employer. \par \par \uc2 Regular competitions enable potential applicants to experience the company's international reach, and to try their hand at managing or developing a brand. \par \par \uc2 PwC, on the other hand, may not have glamour, but experts say the group's consistent presence on campus has allowed it to build up a solid reputation and high profile as a graduate employer. \par \par \uc2 During the survey, another traditional difference between the sexes was identified: confidence and attitudes to money. Male students are far more confident about finding a career-building job and far less concerned about paying off debts that they might have accumulated. This is in spite of the fact that the female students garner the lion's share of top degrees - 59 per cent of first and upper second class degrees are awarded to women. \par \par \uc2 The AGR says employers are sensitive to these differences in confidence, and to the fact that male applicants will tend to overstate their competence, when women will often understate their skills and experience by being "more than honest". \par \par \uc2 But it warns that however much an employer might try to compensate, job selection procedures are competitive, and both interviews and questionnaires will therefore naturally encourage those with what might be called a more "masculine" attitude. \par \par \uc2 At Real World, the student careers website and magazine, Darius Norrell says the different attitudes to debt and to private sector careers may also be down to a greater willingness among men to embrace risk. "Perhaps part of that extra male confidence includes a willingness to tackle a tougher \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ."  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 55938839\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gjob : \uc2 Labor Issues | gcat : \uc2 Political/General N