tell them to cool IT. This is likely to trigger a volcanic outburst that might include rejoinders such as: "What the hell do you know about IT?", "This company is obsessed with cost-reduction", "Nobody loves me" and so on. \par \par \uc2 Once the cathartic effusion has subsided, explain that there has been a slight misunderstanding. You were merely suggesting that focusing on heat management of new technologies might benefit the IT department, the business and even society in general. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 According to one high-profile analyst firm, the powering and associated cooling of new technology amounts to about 60 per cent of the day-to-day running costs of a typical data centre. Hence power management can yield significant savings. \par \par \uc2 But be aware that prior to this realisation, space topped the IT management agenda. Having crammed more technology into smaller boxes, the space issue has receded. \par \par \uc2 Unfortunately, this has resulted in increased energy consumption, given the need to power the cooling systems that keep these tightly packed electronic components from overheating. The net effect being that the space savings have not led to any measurable reduction in the total cost of ownership (TCO) of the data centre. \par \par \uc2 So, once the IT industry warms to a theme, it is nigh on impossible to get it to unclamp its jaw regardless of the rationale. \par \par \uc2 To some extent, the same can be said of the increasing emphasis today on autonomic computing (self managing computers) and virtualisation (squeezing more usage from existing hardware). Both will lead to greater cooling requirements. \par \par \uc2 So how do we encourage the CIO to release his jaw, so to speak? Well, if the IT department can reduce its power consumption, the savings made in the support budget can be redirected into interesting development projects. \par \par \uc2 But perhaps the biggest pay-off is in terms of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which today is a fast growing branch of the public relations industry. There is increasing pressure from the media in respect of global warming. Whether it be for the good of mankind or good brand management, you need to demonstrate environmental sensitivity, and a measure of this is carbon footprint. \par \par \uc2 Thus any initiative within the business that reduces the footprint is likely to find its way into the annual \b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  report. \par \par \uc2 Encourage the CIO to work towards a carbon-neutral IT department. But make it clear that you don't want the server farm to be replaced by wind turbines. \par \par \uc2 This is possibly the most high-profile initiative that the IT department will engage in, and so should appeal to ambitious attention-seeking CIOs. \par \par \uc2 I suggest the CIO is given responsibility for the production of the New Technologies section of the annual CSR report. \par \par \uc2 Manage this carefully, because once the CIO has locked on to this theme it could run out of control. While technologists do not always appear to be socially skilled, they are often very socially conscious and so the bone will be engaged at every level within the IT department. \par \par \uc2 Before you know it, your PC will be replaced by a recycled model, 60 per cent of which comprises unread annual reports and unusable marketing collateral. Given the tropical conditions within the data centre, it could well develop a parallel use as a biosphere for protecting endangered organisms (mainframe operators come to mind). \par \par \uc2 Explain that the CIO will be remunerated on measurable improvements on IT performance per watt of power consumed. This may cause some CIOs to get a little hot under the collar. \par \par \uc2 However it may have the effect of making your competitors greener, whether that be through imitation or plain old envy. \par \par \uc2 * Ade McCormack (ade@auridian.com) is founder of Auridian ( {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.auridian.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.auridian.com}}}\uc2  ), which helps organisations get best value from their IT investment. He is also author of 'IT Demystified - the IT handbook for business professionals' available via {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.auridian.com/book"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.auridian.com/book}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20070509S402.391\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | nanl : \uc2 Analysis | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | c25 : \uc2 Information Technolog