 packaged in bottles made of 95 percent recycled materials.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 And \uc2 Coca-Cola\uc2  plans to cut the plastics in its Dasani water bottles by 7 percent over the next five years, just by tweaking the shape of the bottle and the cap.\par \par \uc2 ''Waste of any kind is inefficiency, and inefficiency equals cost,'' said Scott Vitters, \uc2 Coca-Cola\uc2 's director of sustainable packaging.\par \par \uc2 The number of companies making such changes is growing sharply, as they try to reduce costs and address growing environmental concerns.\par \par \uc2 And their ranks are expected to grow even more, because of \uc2 Wal-Mart Stores\uc2 . The world's largest retailer, known for pressuring vendors to lower their prices, has begun pushing its 66,000 vendors to get rid of excess packaging.\par \par \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  has promised to become ''packaging neutral'' by 2025. That means that, through recycling, reusing or perhaps even composting, it will try to recover as much material as was used in the packaging that flows through its stores.\par \par \uc2 To reach that goal, it is enlisting the help of vendors to cut back on their packaging -- for the products themselves and by using less shrink wrap or cardboard for shipping.\par \par \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  introduced a ''packaging scorecard'' in February that lets vendors rate themselves on criteria like the ratio of package size to product and whether the package uses recycled material. The company may even pay more for products with better packaging, as long as it can recoup the money through recycling revenue or lowered disposal costs.\par \par \uc2 ''The consumer will see the same price, we'll just be getting some of our money at the back end,'' said \uc2 Matt Kistler\uc2 , a senior vice president for Sam's Club, a unit of \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 In fact, many companies began tinkering with their packaging long before \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  entered the fray. They do not expect consumers to buy their products purely for the package -- but they are hoping that ''greener'' packages will give them a competitive edge over similar products, even as they hold down costs.\par \par \uc2 And many companies that do not even distribute through \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  are also pushing to streamline packaging.\par \par \uc2 Estee Lauder\uc2 , for one, spent more than a year working with aluminum smelters to design tubes and caps made from 80 percent recycled aluminum. Much of the packaging of its holiday gift boxes is now made from recycled paper. And its Origins line is expected to soon ship only in folding cartons made with solar, wind or other clean energies.\par \par \uc2 Environmental groups are playing their part, too. Four years ago, Environmental Defense, which was instrumental in getting \uc2 McDonald's\uc2  to give up plastic foam clamshell packages in 1991, devised a calculator that enables package designers to compare the weight, recycled content and performance traits of about 20 materials.\par \par \uc2 Recently, the tool was adopted by GreenBlue, a nonprofit research institute that operates the Sustainable Packaging Coalition. The \uc2 Environmental Protection Agency\uc2  has given GreenBlue a grant of $150,000 to further refine the tool.\par \par \uc2 ''Packaging offers major opportunities for reducing energy use and greenhouse gases, and for saving the $4 billion worth of materials that now ends up in landfills,'' said Matt Hale, director of the agency's Office of Solid Waste.\par \par \uc2 Environmentalists applaud \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2 's involvement, but they want more. Environmental Defense, for example, wants \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  to give greater weight to greenhouse gases emitted when the paper, plastic or other packaging material are made -- and to methane emitted from landfills if the final package is dumped.\par \par \uc2 ''We want them to look harder at the greenhouse gases associated with the package's entire life cycle,'' said \uc2 Gwen Ruta\uc2 , director of corporate partnerships for Environmental Defense, which is working with \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  to upgrade the scorecard.\par \par \uc2 Many suppliers say they welcome the scrutiny from \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2 . \uc2 Nestle Waters North America\uc2 , which owns Poland Spring, Deer Park and other brands, said that it had saved 20 million pounds of paper in the last five years by using narrower labels on many bottles.\par \par \uc2 It recently switched to clear caps that are more easily recycled. And it is rolling out half-liter bottles that contain 12.5 grams of plastics, among the lightest water bottles around.\par \par \uc2 ''I'm pretty sure we'll score an A; let's see if it translates into more business,'' said \uc2 Kim E. Jeffery\uc2 , chief executive of \uc2 Nestle Waters\uc2 , part of \uc2 Nestle\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Many of the easy changes to packages have already been made. Beverage cans are much lighter than they were 10 years ago, and most use recycled aluminum. Deodorants are rarely packed in separate boxes now. Shipping cartons contain large percentages of recycled fiber.\par \par \uc2 But a dearth of municipal programs to collect recyclable materials may hamper further progress. The E.P.A. is trying to persuade local governments that recycling makes economic sense. ''It's a useful argument with city councils,'' Mr. Hale said.\par \par \uc2 Another hurdle is that the need for durable, attractive packaging still bumps up against many plans to make packages green.\par \par \uc2 McDonald's\uc2 , for example, has been steadily reducing the amount of virgin paper and plastic in the boxes that hold its fries and the lids that top its coffee cups.\par \par \uc2 But when it tried shipping toys, cups and other nonfood items to its restaurants in biodegradable packages, the company found they could not withstand the heat inside the trucks. And it had to use more virgin fiber to attain the whiteness of its food bags.\par \par \uc2 ''We're offsetting it with other package reductions, but that white bag is important to the brand,'' said Bob Langert, the vice president for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2 , too, has had to compromise. It tried biobased plastics for the 50-pound bags of dog food it sold at Sam's Club, but they failed to provide an effective barrier to moisture and oxygen. So Sam's has switched to bags made from woven conventional plastics.\par \par \uc2 Even Marcal Paper, which sells paper products made from 100 percent recycled fiber, uses some polyethylene film for packaging. The film is easily molded to the product, and lets the customer see the contents, explained Peter A. Marcalus, a senior vice president.\par \par \uc2 Packages that seem, at first glance, to be environmentally sound can create other problems. When bottles made of biobased plastics like polylactic acid are recycled along with conventional plastic bottles, they create a mix of molecules that is hard to reuse. And reusable containers, be they refillable glass bottles or stainless steel canisters, require a lot of energy to transport and to clean for reuse.\par \par \uc2 Consumer behavior presents its own challenges, since smaller packages can appear to be more expensive than those with more packaging.\par \par \uc2 Coke recently redesigned its classic contour bottles to be lighter and more impact-resistant. The new bottle looks smaller. ''Our challenge is persuading consumers that they are getting the same volume in a better bottle,'' Mr. Vitters said.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Jeffery of \uc2 Nestle Waters\uc2  said the company would begin an education campaign around its new bottles to ''make sure that customers don't think the bottles feel lighter because they hold less water.''\par \par \uc2 And sometimes, aesthetics will trump environmentalism in the end, anyway. That recycled aluminum that \uc2 Estee Lauder\uc2  fought so hard for does not shine up well, and some of the brands refuse to use it.\par \par \uc2 ''That shiny cap is part of Clinique's brand image,'' said John A. Delfausse, vice president for package development at \uc2 Estee Lauder\uc2 . ''And they will not switch.''\par \par \uc2 Photos (Photographs by Anthony Cenicola/The New York Times)(pg. C9)\par \par \uc2 Chart: ''Shrink Wrapping''\par \par \uc2 Examples of packages that have been redesigned to use less or different material, while still holding the same amount of product.\par \par \uc2 Coca-Cola\par \par \uc2 CHANGES -- \uc2 Coca-Cola\uc2  redesigned the bottle to make it smaller and lighter.\par \par \uc2 SAVINGS -- Materials and transportation costs.\par \par \uc2 Crest\par \par \uc2 CHANGES -- \uc2 Procter & Gamble\uc2  introduced a stand-alone rigid tube.\par \par \uc2 SAVINGS -- Eliminated box that most toothpastes still come in.\par \par \uc2 Nestle\par \par \uc2 CHANGES -- \uc2 Nestle\uc2  redesigned the bottle and cap to make them lighter and more recyclable. Also narrowed the label by half an inch.\par \par \uc2 SAVINGS -- Uses 30 percent less plastic, and less paper for the label.\par \par \uc2 McDonald's\par \par \uc2 CHANGES -- In the early 1990s, \uc2 McDonald's\uc2  replaced plastic foam clamshell sandwich holders with recyclable cardboard.\par \par \uc2 SAVINGS -- Biodegradable.\par \par \uc2 (Source by The companies)(pg. C9)\par \par \uc2 Drawing (Illustration by The New York Times)(pg. C1) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15