0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 A computer has roughly the same environmental impact as a refrigerator. The difference is that, in the developed world at least, the number of fridges being sold has been fairly static over the past few years. \par \par \uc2 Use of computers, however, has exploded at work, in the home and even in cars. The result is that IT is a significant and measurable consumer of energy. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 IBM, for example, estimates that the power demanded worldwide by computing data centres currently stands at 100bn kilowatt hours a year, and that data centres are one of the fastest-growing users of power. \par \par \uc2 Research published in February by Jonathan Koomey, a consulting professor at Stanford University, found that total power used by servers represented 0.6 per cent of total US electricity consumption in 2005. \par \par \uc2 With the power needed for cooling and other auxiliary services added on, Prof Koomey calculates that electricity use rises to 1.2 per cent, equivalent to the power used by all the country's colour televisions. Moreover, he calculates that aggregate electricity use for servers doubled between 2000 and 2005. Most of this came from businesses installing large numbers of new servers. \par \par \uc2 Such figures put businesses in a quandary. On the one hand, they need to handle more transactions in less time, process and store more data and automate more business processes. All this demands more computing power. \par \par \uc2 On the other hand, they face practical and ethical constraints on their ability to do this. \par \par \uc2 IT is increasingly coming under scrutiny, not just from \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  advocates, but also from the board for its power use. With energy prices high in historic terms, CFOs want to see power used more sparingly by IT. And in practical terms, CIOs might not even have access to the power they need. \par \par \uc2 "Even where there is overall capacity in the grid, there are more localised problems," says Mark Bramfitt, principal programme manager in \uc2 Pacific Gas and Electric Company\uc2 's customer energy efficiency group. "If a company needs five megawatts of power it takes time to design and build that supply." \par \par \uc2 These social, financial and practical constraints have prompted businesses to start to think about how they can reduce energy use from IT, or at least rein in its growth. \par \par \uc2 A survey just published by \uc2 Forrester Research\uc2  examined attitudes to "green" computing among corporate IT purchasers. \par \par \uc2 Most IT professionals said they expected green factors to have an impact on their future purchasing decisions. But at the same time, most respondents said they were hearing little from top-tier manufacturers about green initiatives, and that they would only invest in more environmentally friendly equipment if it also provided a hard financial return on investment. \par \par \uc2 "The metrics that CIOs and IT departments are measured on are not based on energy savings," says Chris Mines, senior vice president at Forrester and author of the research. "They might not even be aware of energy consumption. They are measured on uptime, throughput and mean time between failures. This encourages energy consumption and server proliferation, as CIOs try to build systems that are bullet proof." \par \par \uc2 CIOs are, Mines adds, necessarily cautious about interfering with IT systems that are working well. Unless businesses change the way they measure the performance of their IT departments, CIOs will be reluctant to swap out old equipment for newer, greener alternatives or even make significant changes to the way it is used or managed. "There is a built-in conservatism which creates barriers to introducing new technology, even though the arithmetic would say there is a tangible return on investment," suggests Mines. \par \par \uc2 This is despite the fact that a number of mainstream IT vendors, including \uc2 Sun Microsystems\uc2 , IBM and \uc2 Hewlett-Packard\uc2  have been working on energy-efficient initiatives for several years and for some projects, more than a decade. \par \par \uc2 However, the driver for such work was often the need to cope with limited power availability, rather than the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  per se. Much early work carried out by HP on data centre cooling, for example, was to meet the needs of the US military. \par \par \uc2 "When other customers were interested, it was mostly because of the total cost of ownership or because the CIO was being bugged by the operations and facilities group for building data centres using energy that was increasingly expensive," recalls John Frey, worldwide director, corporate environmental strategies at HP. \par \par \uc2 "But in the past three to four years we have seen the conversation evolve from a total cost of ownership conversation to one of power and cooling, driven by heat loads. We also have customers who want to be carbon neutral, and they need the IT department to contribute to that." \par \par \uc2 How businesses do that in practice remains very much open to debate. A number of IT hardware companies appear to be advocating the large-scale replacement of server and desktop computer hardware. \par \par \uc2 While this should bring down running costs - and may be the only option for companies where power and cooling constraints are limiting expansion in the data centre - the environmental justification is harder to make. \par \par \uc2 "For a computer, 75 per cent of the environmental impact occurs before it is even switched on," says Tony Roberts, CEO of Computer Aid International, a charity that collects PCs for re-use in the developing world. "If you prolong the life of a PC for another three to four years, you can halve its environmental footprint." \par \par \uc2 He adds that it is only recently that companies have moved away from "thinking that throwing computers into skips is normal business practice". \par \par \uc2 Replacing working computers simply because of their energy use brings with it the environmental cost of disposal and the environmental impact of the new machine, as well as disruption to the IT infrastructure. As a result, CIOs are starting to look at other ways to increase the output of IT systems for a given power load. \par \par \uc2 Tools in use range from more intelligent cooling in the data centre, virtualisation, and better IT management tools. \par \par \uc2 Virtualisation can bring quick results, as a server running at 80 per cent capacity uses only marginally more power than one running with just a 20 per cent load. \par \par \uc2 IBM has developed water cooling systems that can attach to individual racks of equipment to eliminate hotspots, removing the need to chill the whole room, and the company's latest Project Green initiative allows IT managers to "throttle back" systems that are running hot, according to Rich Lechner, vice-president for IT optimisation at IBM. \par \par \uc2 "More effective design of the data centre itself also has a lot of potential for companies to reduce or maintain their carbon footprints while increasing capacity," he says. \par \par \uc2 But CIOs' ability to act in this area is being hampered by the lack of global or even regional standards governing the environmental footprint of IT gear. \par \par \uc2 "Right now, we don't know the relative environmental impact of our morning cup of coffee or of using IT," warns Cindy Cahill, a partner at professional services firm Deloitte. "Until we get some meaningful standards it's hard to make any comparisons within IT or between IT and other industries." Independent CSR and environmental auditing can help, but for the most part it deals with data after the event. \par \par \uc2 There is, though, more that IT departments can do with better use of management tools, and by raising awareness among employees of the environmental consequences of how they work. \par \par \uc2 HP, for example, automatically enabled the power-saving function on its 150,000-plus PC network, yet received just 13 complaints from staff. Companies such as Pacific Gas and Electricity are also working to educate customers about "phantom loads": devices such as phone and laptop chargers or displays left plugged in or on standby when not in use. \par \par \uc2 "I am convinced there is more to be gained through behavioural change than through architectural change or swapping out equipment in the IT organisation or on users' desks," says Forrester's Mr Mines. " \par \par \uc2 Organisations that keep their PCs running 24x7 are still out there."  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\wi