become the first media company to become carbon neutral, it went about implementing the policy with typical single-mindedness. Within five months, it had hit the target - the satellite broadcaster now uses 100 per cent renewable electricity for all \uc2 BSkyB\uc2 -owned UK sites and has involved all its departments, staff and suppliers in reducing carbon emissions. \par \par \uc2 James Murdoch, chief executive, saw the policy as part of a push to educate customers about ways of reducing their impact on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as well as showing its values were in tune with their concerns. The importance of this leadership role has been recognised with a "big tick" for \uc2 BSkyB\uc2  in this year's Business in the Community (BITC) awards for excellence where the leading theme is climate change. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The consequences of the satellite broadcaster's move went much further, however, when Rupert Murdoch, the 75-year-old chairman and chief executive of \uc2 News Corporation\uc2 , announced that the rest of his media empire would follow the example set by his son and heir apparent at \uc2 BSkyB.\par \par \uc2 The fact that Mr Murdoch was previously seen as a sceptic on global warming was a telling indicator of the degree to which business now accepts that the argument over whether climate change is happening is over - even if there is still debate over its exact causes and the appropriate remedies. \par \par \uc2 Peter Newman, the BITC awards director, describes this as the climate change effect: "Business is surging into an area that for decades was the worthy but distinctly unsexy preserve of compliance, risk management and environmental management systems, in a search for new products, new markets and new ways of doing things." \par \par \uc2 Nine other companies have been recognised by BITC this year in the new Man Group International Climate Change Award for strategic, comprehensive and innovative approaches to tackling climate change. They include Tesco, Barclays and B&Q, but also companies such as \uc2 Lafarge\uc2  Cement for whom the reduction of carbon emissions presents a great challenge. \par \par \uc2 In the Eco-efficiency Award category, big ticks have gone to Toyota for reducing water use by 72 per cent (after reducing waste to landfill to zero), Ford, which has massively reduced use of oils and cooling fluids and production of waste sludges at Dagenham and GEDA, a Northern Ireland construction company building high quality homes with energy saving built in. \par \par \uc2 Elsewhere in the house-building industry, Redrow has introduced a new-style home for first-time buyers with high environmental specification that sells for just Pounds 60,000. \par \par \uc2 ScotAsh, a joint venture between \uc2 ScottishPower\uc2  and \uc2 Lafarge\uc2 , has developed a way of processing the waste from coal-fired power generation so it can be used in concretes and aggregates rather than poured into landfill. \par \par \uc2 Both have been awarded big ticks in the TCS Marketplace Innovation category for products and services that meet social or environmental needs. \par \par \uc2 This year is the 10th year of the awards, which have been gathering strength over the years with entries rising from 141 in 2002 to 425 this year. \par \par \uc2 For Julia Cleverdon, BITC chief executive, the improved quality and sophistication of this year's awards entries shows the growing maturity of corporate responsibility as a central and integral aspect of modern business practice. "Companies are getting smarter and bolder in the way they operate as responsible businesses," she says. \par \par \uc2 To mark the 25th anniversary of the founding of BITC, a Jubilee Award has been introduced for companies whose \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  programmes have made a long-term impact on communities over the decade of the awards. Big ticks have gone to 42 businesses, ranging from Manchester City football club and Red Dragon FM to corporate giants such as BT and Royal Mail. \par \par \uc2 The most popular category this year is the \uc2 Merrill Lynch\uc2  Raising Achievement of Young People Award with 60 new entries. \par \par \uc2 Ticks have been awarded to 27, with 21 more re-accredited. This reflects the long involvement of companies in supporting education and schools - in poll after poll, business puts education at the top of the list of priorities for corporate community investment. \par \par \uc2 Eleven companies have been commended for their impact on society, which recognises leadership integration of responsible business practices. \par \par \uc2 Nancy Turrell, corporate responsibility manager for \uc2 J. Sainsbury\uc2 , which also has big ticks in two other categories, says the benchmarking offered by the BITC awards is helpful in focusing big businesses on what the outside world is demanding of them. \par \par \uc2 "Our community programmes have become stronger every year, despite the tough trading conditions Sainsbury's has been experiencing," she says. "That's a real source of pride for the business and our colleagues who live in the communities we serve." \par \par \uc2 Perhaps counter to popular views of the industry, the mining sector is one of the top-performing ones in BITC's annual corporate responsibility index. Andrew Vickerman of Rio Tinto says his company - also a recipient of a big tick for its impact on society - says investors are increasingly interested in such indices. \par \par \uc2 "We operate in communities in sensitive locations and handling these issues is central to our business success. If we did not do so sensitively, we would risk losing the licence we have to work in those communities - which are also where our employees live." \par \par \uc2 However, private equity remains the notable exception to the growing recognition of the importance of the \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  agenda, according to Ms Cleverdon. \par \par \uc2 "Despite encouraging signs that the private equity houses and their portfolio companies are beginning to engage meaningfully in the responsible business agenda, they are most conspicuous by their absence from our awards and other indices."  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20070531L114.015\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 bsbro : \uc2 British Sky Broadcasting Group PLC\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clver