All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Banks are firmly in the lower divisions when it comes to greenhouse gas emissions. Power stations burn coal or gas, chemicals companies have factories that may spew out gases, steelmakers have huge power needs. Even farmers have a bigger "carbon footprint" than financial services. \par \par \uc2 For modern banks, most of whose business goes on in cyber space, heating and lighting their branches and offices, and powering their IT systems may be their biggest contributions to global warming. But banks have been at the forefront of cutting their emissions, and now they are using their experience to help their clients to do the same. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 A lengthening list of banks and other financial institutions have recently decided to become "carbon neutral". HSBC was the first, and it has been followed by Barclays, Aviva, the hedge fund Man Group and the Co-operative Group. Many other banks have pledged to cut their emissions substantially, including \uc2 Citigroup\uc2 , the world's biggest financial services group, which in May said it would increase from $1bn to $10bn its investment in lowering its greenhouse gas output. \par \par \uc2 Stephen Green, group chairman of HSBC, acknowledges: "In financial services, it is relatively easy [to go carbon neutral]." \par \par \uc2 Banks going carbon-neutral generally do so because it burnishes their reputations, cuts down on waste and so can help to save money, and fulfils their \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  criteria, as well as presenting a more human face to the public. HSBC, for instance, has been using its green credentials?in?its advertising as a draw to customers, both benefiting from and fostering the growing green awareness among consumers. \par \par \uc2 Companies in other sectors are now following the banks' lead: \uc2 BSkyB\uc2  said it would be carbon neutral last year, followed by \uc2 News Corp\uc2  this year; PwC, \uc2 Marks and Spencer\uc2 , \uc2 Reckitt Benckiser\uc2  and \uc2 Yahoo\uc2  have also made the pledge. \par \par \uc2 Carbon neutrality means that a company has reduced its negative impact on the climate to zero. This is done by cutting greenhouse gas emissions as far as possible, usually by reducing energy wastage in the first place, and then by satisfying the remainder of the company's electricity needs with renewable energy. This can take the form of putting solar panels and wind turbines on company premises, but companies can also enter "green tariff" agreements with electricity suppliers, by which the generator will invest in renewable energy plants sufficient to supply the energy the company uses. \par \par \uc2 When a company has taken these steps, typically some unavoidable emissions will be still be left, such as those caused by corporate travel. In this case, the company can "offset" its remaining emissions by buying carbon credits from a reputable supplier. \par \par \uc2 The Co-operative Group\uc2  has even gone one step further, and has become "carbon positive". Paul Monaghan, head of ethics and sustainability for the Co-operative Group, explains that the company is buying offsets equal to 110 per cent of emissions, in order to make up for its past environmental impact. "As far as we know, we are the only ones who are carbon positive but maybe others will join us." \par \par \uc2 But offsetting should only ever be used as a last resort, warns Pablo Ceppi, strategy manager at \uc2 the Carbon Trust\uc2 , a UK government-funded body charged with helping businesses to reduce their emissions. "You have to ensure you have cut back your environmental impact as far as possible first," he advises. Otherwise, instead of truly minimising its environmental damage, the company is simply displacing it. \par \par \uc2 Environmental campaigners have begun to criticise the practice of offsetting for that reason, arguing that companies are pretending to be green by buying carbon credits while continuing to pollute. Charlie Kronick, campaigner at Greenpeace, says: "Companies seem to want to use it as a get-out-of-jail-free card." \par \par \uc2 Companies should also take care to spread their good practice. "There is a boundary issue with being carbon neutral," says Mr Ceppi. He explains that a company's direct emissions - those caused by its own business activities, such as its energy use - may only be a small part of its contribution to global warming, because its indirect emissions - those generated by its supply chain and customers - may be far greater.  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha