lvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FTCOM\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2007 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 When Rosa Chun dec-ided to test the claim that happy staff make happy customers, she made two discoveries: first, many managers believed it so implicitly that they saw no reason to research it. Second, there is no empirical evidence for such a claim. \par \par \uc2 Ms Chun is a professor of business ethics and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  at Manchester Business School. For her study, she interviewed 10,000 people (half were customer-facing staff, half were customers) at 13 UK retail organisations in financial services, food retailing, telecommunications and insurance. She asked: how satisfied they were, whether they would recommend a friend to work for the company or buy its products, and so on. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Some business units revealed a positive correlation between happy staff and happy customers. But there were others where staff were happy but customers unhappy, or where customers were happy but staff were not. "Most managers believe the link because they have read some books," Prof Chun says. "But when you dig into their actual experience, they have very little evidence." \par \par \uc2 Companies have invested vast amounts of time and money over the past decade on the assumption that it is true. Team-building exercises, employee empowerment initiatives, "live-the-brand" campaigns, culture change programmes and perks such as at-work massage or ping-pong tables - has all this effort and expense been squandered? \par \par \uc2 Sadly, it is a possibility. Biannual research by the human resources consultancy \uc2 Towers Perrin\uc2 , for example, has found no sustained rise in employee engagement levels across Europe. Gallup's Q12 benchmarking survey, which now covers more than 500,000 work groups in more than 450 companies in 124 countries, shows similar findings. Over the past seven years, it repeatedly found that no more than about 30 per cent of employees are actively "engaged" in their jobs and one in five are positively disengaged. \par \par \uc2 "Many people adopted the principle but they had trouble making it stick," concedes Earl Sasser, a professor at Harvard Business School and co-author in 1997 of one of the original books - The Service Profit Chain: How leading companies link profit and growth to loyalty, satisfaction, and value - to promote the happy staff/happy customers theory. "Linking customer satisfaction back to employee behaviours is tough to do," he says. \par \par \uc2 The cause-and-effect relationship between employee loyalty, productivity and customer satisfaction "was never as strong as we hoped", adds his co-author and fellow HBS professor James Heskett. \par \par \uc2 In other words, the original and influential theory, which linked employee satisfaction to employee loyalty to productivity to customer satisfaction to customer loyalty to profitability in a direct causal chain, now lies in tatters. The connections are "not as linear as we once thought", admits Peter Flade, managing partner at Gallup. \par \par \uc2 If anything, however, this just makes organisations search harder for the elusive connection between staff and customer happiness. \par \par \uc2 Separate research by Prof Chun, for example, suggests that ifemployees are more satisfied than customers with the company, profits tend to rise, whereas if customers are happier than staff, profits tend to sag. That is because employee attitudes rub off on customers over time, she suggests. \par \par \uc2 Profs Sasser and Heskett are, meanwhile, working on a new "science of delight". "It is process quality that links employees to customers," says Prof Heskett - how you do things matters. Successful companies focus with "laser precision" on the staff behaviours that customers want and give their emp-loy-ees a sense of "ownership" (as distinct from satisfaction, loyalty, commitment or engagement) so they can demonstrate "latitude within limits" when dealing with customers, he says. \par \par \uc2 Other companies are delving in detail to find exactly what links staff to customer happiness, and what does not. When Gallup analysed its Q12 database, whichcorrelates employee engagement to customer engagement, for example, it concluded that centrally inspired and directed motivation and change initiatives mostly fall on deaf ears. As a rule, Gallup concluded, employees do not trust mes-sages emanating from head offices, but they do respond to people if they can look into their eyes: that is, their own supervisors. \par \par \uc2 This kind of finding is prompting companies such as Tesco and Standard Chartered Bank (see below) to focus intensively on improving staff/supervisor interactions. "We know that 'the way I am with my boss' is a key determinant in the level of staff loyalty towards Tesco," says Maxine Dolan, Tesco group training manager. "The store manager and his/her team create the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  in each store." \par \par \uc2 Now more fundamental challenges to the "service profit chain theory" are brewing. The very idea of trying to motivate staff to run that extra mile for customers starts at the wrong end of the stick, argue proponents of so-called lean methods. Instead, companies should start with a deep un-derstanding of what customers want, and work with their staff to make it as easy as possible for them to deliver the goods. "There is no evidence that happy cows make better milk, and there never will be," says Jeffrey Liker, professor of industrial and operations engineering at the University of Michigan. However, fresh from making a study of "talent development" by Japanese company Toyota, he argues that the Toyota philosophy that no one comes to work to do a job, they come to work to learn how to do the job better, satisfies all theories of human motivation (rewards, feedback, recognition, opportunity to learn, sense of autonomy etc). \par \par \uc2 One organisation trying to apply such lean methods is Bolton NHS Trust in the UKWe are trying to redesign the work we do back from our [patients] rather than forwards from our staff," says David Fillingham, chief executive. Staff are happier for it, he insists. "Reducing paperwork for staff in the stroke unit by 42 per cent makes their job easier, so they're happier." They are also happier when they see patients getting a better service. And they're more motivated if they have been involved in redesigning the process." \par \par \uc2 None of these app-roaches is necessarily contradictory. But none of them fits the service profit chain either. The search for a successor is under way. \par \par \uc2 Standard Chartered: focus on supervisor/staff interactions \par \par \uc2 When it comes to motivation, it is the people you deal with daily who count. This insight has transformed the way Standard Chartered Bank approaches performance improvement. \par \par \uc2 Every year, it sends a questionnaire developed by Gallup to all staff asking them 12 questions such as 'Do you know what is expected of you at work?', 'Is there someone at work who encourages your development?' and 'At work do your opinions seem to count?'. \par \par \uc2 The answers provide data on the 4,000 teams working in the bank, and invariably show widely varying levels of engagement even when HR processes are exactly the same. "It is down to the managers," says Peter Miller, the bank's director of people, property and assurance. \par \par \uc2 He is using the survey as a tool to improve engagement levels and, he believes, performance. Survey results are reported to supervisors as a scorecard. Supervisors are required to meet their staff for an 'impact planning' session, where scores for one or two of the questions (for example, 'Do your opinions seem to count?') are prioritised for improvement. \par \par \uc2 There is a strong correlation between engagement levels and performance levels of teams, says Mr Miller. Staff in the most engaged teams are 50 per cent less likely than others to leave the bank, and the most engaged teams are 15-20 per cent more productive than the least in terms of revenue and profit growth.  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 56693801\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 towpfc : \uc2 Towers, Perrin, Forster & Crosby, Inc.\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b