six years, the mail systems pioneer \uc2 Pitney Bowes\uc2  has acquired more than 65 companies, all on the watch of Michael Critelli, chief executive at the time and now executive chairman. \par \par \uc2 He has been systematically refocusing the business, transforming it from the collection of diverse businesses he found when he joined the legal department 28 years ago. His goal is to make the Connecticut-based group a leader in the "mailstream" marketplace - everything connected with the creation and distribution of letters and packages. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Non-core activities have been cut away; the acquisitions are only in areas where \uc2 Pitney Bowes\uc2 , inventor of the postage stamping machine, intends to vie for market leadership. \par \par \uc2 Now the intention is to integrate the new businesses seamlessly into \uc2 Pitney Bowes\uc2 ' central systems. Over the past decade, the company has installed SAP enterprise software to handle the back office, and Siebel's customer relationship management software for customer-facing functions. \par \par \uc2 But as Mr Critelli admits, integration is rarely simple or easy. "Because of allthe acquisitions we have made, we are probably not any closer to having anintegrated, enterprise-wide system than we were 10 years ago. \par \par \uc2 "At the same time as we were integrating businesses we owned prior to 2001, we were adding new businesses. One of the challenges our new chief executive, Murray Martin, has to grapple with is how to accelerate the integration process to take full advantage of the synergies we bring to the businesses we acquire." \par \par \uc2 Mr Martin may have an advantage in having been the group's operations director and enjoying an enviable credibility with the group's information technology specialists. \par \par \uc2 However, 58-year-old Mr Critelli, with six patents to his name and more pending, is himself no stranger to technology. He invented a method of embedding magnetic codes in postage stamps to prevent their re-use and a way of marking packages with invisible ink to label their contents. The invisible ink technology is, he thinks, something the industry will adopt. \par \par \uc2 His background, however, is law. After undergraduate studies in communications and political science at the University of Wisconsin, he took a law degree at Harvard Law School and became a trial lawyer, a barrister in UK parlance. This gave him two invaluable skills - the ability to absorb a new body of knowledge and communicate it quickly and concisely - "I learned neither to be afraid of, nor defer to, experts" - and adaptability. \par \par \uc2 As a lawyer, however, he found his core values too often at variance with those of his clients and in 1979 joined the legal department of \uc2 Pitney Bowes.\uc2  He was one of the first top trial lawyers to opt for a career in commercial law. \par \par \uc2 His first substantial contact with IT, however, was in 1990. Having been promoted to General Counsel, he also took on responsibility for safety, the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and human resources. \par \par \uc2 The human resources department was changing systems, from what he describes as an "outsourced and very paper-driven benefits process" to a flexible benefits programme which gave staff considerably more choice. It involved the integration of personnel data, medical benefits data and payroll. He was also involved in improving storage and retrieval systems for the legal department. \par \par \uc2 After his appointment as chief executive in 1997, alongside reshaping the company and improving profitability, Mr Critelli has been whittling down the multiple IT systems. \par \par \uc2 The company has a chief information officer who is not on the board but who reports to the chief executive. There are regular meetings to discuss progress: "It is a big problem. We have a lot of legacy support systems that we would like to retire. There is confusion among our customers because our businesses market under multiple brand names. \par \par \uc2 "But we are far ahead of where we were six or seven years ago. Our marketing materials have a common look and feel. Our billing statements are starting to have a common look and feel and our financial reporting is much better integrated." \par \par \uc2 A problem common to many businesses that have grown rapidly by acquisition is that the multiplicity of IT systems they have inherited are perfectly efficient in their own way. \par \par \uc2 Mr Critelli says: "Many of our customers and specific parts of our business have customised needs that a generic system cannot easily meet. Typically, there is a trade-off between what is good for an individual business and its customers and what is good for the whole of \uc2 Pitney Bowes.\uc2 " \par \par \uc2 He gives the example of the systems \uc2 Pitney Bowes\uc2  uses to enable customers to order supplies of goods of various kinds and pay for them. \par \par \uc2 Because of acquisitions, there are six or seven separate order entry and billing systems in place. Each is designed to enable the supplies call centre to record orders, process them and fulfill the order at the optimum speed. \par \par \uc2 "If you were to integrate the six into a common system, each ordering and billing process would take longer, so transaction volumes would go down," Mr Critelli points out. \par \par \uc2 "On the other hand, you would only have one system to maintain, so IT costs would be lower and billing errors reduced. Furthermore, customers would find it simpler to do business with us. \par \par \uc2 "But if you look at the pure unallocated costs of the businesses, it is always best to have a proprietary systems for each business: that's the trade-off we have to make. We have to do a better job of understanding the total allocated costs of doing business in a very decentralised way." \par \par \uc2 In his new role, Mr Critelli will focus on new opportunities for the company stemming from postal reform in the US and abroad and inits chosen areas of healthcare, government services and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2 He will inevitably have less contact with the IT department, but he understands the dangers of spreading himself too thinly: "I realised I was not leveraging my time as effectively as I could." \par \par \uc2 And he is enthusiastic about the capabilities of his successor as CEO: "Murray Martin has said we will integrate a lot faster than we used to. Because he comes from operations and because he used to be on the other side of this argument, he has a lot of credibility. \par \par \uc2 "So I think he is goingto be more effectivebecause he is a guy who is universally regarded as an excellent operating person. The other operating people will follow his leadership and get this job donefaster than I would have been able to."  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20070613S206.300\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\f