dctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 A Silver Jubilee is usually a time for celebration. For a campaigning organisation such as Business in the Community (BITC), whose remit is to drive corporate responsibility in the UK, it is also an appropriate occasion to examine successes, failures and challenges. \par \par \uc2 The climate in which business operates is very different from that of 25 years ago, when a small group of companies set out to help regenerate communities hit by unemployment and neglect that had exploded in inner-city riots in 1981. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The first companies to be involved in the non-profit campaign included 3i, IBM, and Marks and Spencer. Long before "\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 " had become established in the business lexicon, BITC was pioneering activities such as community volunteering. \par \par \uc2 Today, signing up to corporate responsibility is de rigueur for big businesses. Executives around the world agree that companies should play a wider social role beyond generating high returns for shareholders. Concerns about climate change, data privacy, pension sustainability, and the economic and social impact of outsourcing and offshoring, have made their way inexorably on to the boardroom agenda - although business leaders still struggle with how to respond. \par \par \uc2 What has been the contribution of BITC, one of the world's oldest corporate responsibility campaigning groupss, to all this? Since its beginnings in community work, it has extended its reach to cover the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and companies' relationship with consumers, for example, through responsible drinking campaigns or cause-related marketing. \par \par \uc2 In the past few years, the charity has pushed the case for responsibility to be treated as an integral part of the way companies do business, not an optional extra. \par \par \uc2 "BITC has helped make the UK the undisputed global leader in the practice of responsible business and in terms of the sophistication of debate on corporate responsibility," says David Grayson, a BITC director and head of the new Doughty Centre for Corporate Responsibility at Cranfield School of Management. \par \par \uc2 Prof Grayson has researched the lessons learned over the past quarter century in a study published this month for BITC and the CSR Initiative at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government. \par \par \uc2 While he acknowledges that he is not a dispassionate outsider, his study reflects frank views from interviews with more than 200 people - including past and current staff and board members, business and political figures, NGOs and media commentators - and from seminars he has held. \par \par \uc2 Winning the commitment of top business leaders to the cause of corporate responsibility is seen as the campaign's biggest achievement, he says. He quotes one interviewee as saying that BITC has made it "socially acceptable for business leaders to admit [that corporate responsibility] is important". Its big campaigns are fronted by business figures. The charity, whose president is the Prince of Wales, also works closely with government. \par \par \uc2 Under Julia Cleverdon, its irrepressible chief executive for the past 15 years, BITC has used the power of persuasion to great effect. Its "Seeing is Believing" visits, designed to open business people's hearts and minds to problems such as homelessness and youth unemployment, are regarded as a big success, as is its emphasis on spreading good practice. \par \par \uc2 The organisation also wins plaudits for forging partnerships with the public and voluntary sectors, introducing a competitive element to being responsible, and gaining a high profile through media tie-ups such as that with the Financial Times for the annual Awards for Excellence. \par \par \uc2 In 1990, Tim (now Lord) Bell, the public relations guru, told BITC that it had to create the "Oscars of Responsible Business". The glitzy award ceremony in the Royal Albert Hall fits that bill - even if, privately, not every business leader is entirely comfortable with this method of self-congratulation. \par \par \uc2 Where could the organisation have done better? While it has been strong on creating campaigns and programmes, these are not always implemented effectively, says Prof Grayson. There is also criticism that involvement in so many issues prevents it from delivering a clear message or spotting big new trends in corporate responsibility, such as climate change. \par \par \uc2 Some topical concerns, such as executive pay and corporate lobbying, have remained no-go areas for BITC. Its record on collaborating with business schools is described as patchy. \par \par \uc2 As to whether BITC has pushed its 750 members hard enough, views vary. "A lot of critics of business see corporate responsibility as a fig-leaf and feel that because BITC hasn't been tougher with some companies at an earlier stage on some issues it has given credence to that argument," says, Prof Grayson. \par \par \uc2 "But other people have said that it has been a leadership organisation, not a representative organisation, and it's been good at that. There's a challenge that a membership organisation can go only so far ahead of where the mass of members are. But the decision to inspire rather than to bludgeon was a conscious one." \par \par \uc2 The tension between its campaigning role and its delivery of programmes has led to a debate over its future. It is likely that the organisation will rely more heavily on specialist strategic allies to implement projects on a bigger scale, rather than try to do everything inhouse. It is already working with organisations such as The Carbon Trust on climate change. \par \par \uc2 But BITC is not likely to abandon programme delivery entirely in favour of being a pure think-tank. "There's a recognition that you don't have the credibility or the ability to spot better ways to do things, if you're not doing some delivery," says Prof Grayson. \par \par \uc2 Another key challenge is the changing nature of business ownership. Its work to date has mainly been with large listed companies. A new project, led by Stephen Howard, managing director, is examining the growth of private equity and its implications for corporate responsibility. \par \par \uc2 There is also potential for greater collaboration between BITC and international bodies such as the United Nations Global Compact and the Global Reporting Initiative, says Prof Grayson. He adds: "Given the enormity of challenges such as climate change, the clash of values, social exclusion, and poverty, a greater sense of urgency is needed among businesses, and BITC has to communicate this."  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \