l about using numbers to provide information. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  is currently a somewhat fuzzier concept but, as it enters mainstream business decision-making, accountants can - and should - play a key role. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 This week, CSR comes of age at the Global Compact Leaders' Summit being held in Geneva. Convened by the United Nations, it is an international gathering of business leaders, government ministers and heads of civil society. \par \par \uc2 Key business issues to be discussed include the corporate approach to customers, employees, supply chains, communities and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2 Accountants have an important role to play here. They can help to build the business case for actions to be taken - and better measure and present the results of actions taken. \par \par \uc2 Communicating CSR analysis and results to stakeholders is becoming as routine as financial reporting. Where do the data sit? Who is the owner? Why is it measured and how is it measured? Can the data be meaningfully consolidated or averaged? What drives the measure and what does it in turn drive? Is there external benchmarking data and what are suitable tolerance levels beyond which exceptions are flagged? \par \par \uc2 Accountants already address these questions for financial data and are beginning to apply the same principles and standards to non-financial data. \par \par \uc2 Unlike financial reporting, CSR draws on a much wider range of data and information, including subjects as diverse as CO emissions and energy consumption, business air travel miles, video and teleconference usage, as well as staff analysis and even paper usage. \par \par \uc2 Controls and disciplines that are the norm for financial data may not yet exist for CSR data. There are many questions to be asked. Is the information complete? Is it accurate? Is it being measured consistently? Are CSR targets and goals aligned to, and supporting, strategic objectives? \par \par \uc2 So what do accountants have to offer in supporting the development of good CSR? \par \par \uc2 First, the finance function already has in place processes to gather information from across the organisation and store it in a structured and accessible way. The knowledge of how these processes work is already being applied to non-financial data to improve quality, timeliness and accuracy of information. \par \par \uc2 Second, the investment community and ratings agencies are taking increasing interest in the impact of non-financial measures on sustainability. The disciplines of finance provide the necessary rigour and control to establish robust and repeatable reporting, demonstrating progress against CSR targets. \par \par \uc2 Third, leading indicators, such as investment in the community, and lagging indicators, such as customer satisfaction and trust, now form part of performance to be monitored against targets and strategic goals. \par \par \uc2 Stakeholders are watching closely to see how longer-term goals are being addressed. \par \par \uc2 The challenge to deliver against these goals rests with the business as a whole but the finance team has a key role to ensure that accurate, timely and consistent analysis is presented. \par \par \uc2 Geoff Booth is a practice director, financial services, at Parson Consulting  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\t