m\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Chris Watt, manager of the Pounds 60m Jupiter Environmental Income fund, says there is a "healthy amount of evidence that companies are doing more rather than just saying they're doing more" when it comes to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 He describes BT as a corporate leader in this regard, it having reduced its carbon emissions by 60 per cent in a decade and aiming to reduce them by 80 per cent.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 But BT's real attraction for Jupiter's fund lies elsewhere: specifically in an attractive prospective price/earnings ratio of 14 based on next year's forecasts and a high dividend yield of 4.5 per cent. Mr Watt adds that the general perception that BT is a company in ongoing decline fails to take proper account of its advances internationally and in the "broadband space".\par \par \uc2 Mr Watt describes hisvalue-based stock-picking as "no different to any other fund" in its hunt for returns. "We won't just hold stocks that are green, we hold them because we think they'll make money," he says.\par \par \uc2 Hundreds of UK companies are automatically available for investment by the fund, having been already approved by the Jupiter SRI & Governance team of environmental and social scientists. But the fund will not invest in oil, mining, nuclear, tobacco or armament companies, so excluding a significant proportion of its benchmark index, the FTSE All-Share.\par \par \uc2 With oil and mining firms strong recently, the portfolio has underperformed in the short term, although "small green stocks have taken up the slack".\par \par \uc2 More generally, Jupiter Environmental Income - which is termed a "light green" fund - tends to have a bias towards small and medium caps, which has helped its performance in the past couple of years. The fund will also increase its FTSE 100 weighting where the manager can find value and to help with its income remit. The current yield is about 2.8 per cent.\par \par \uc2 As well as telecoms, Mr Watt is overweight in transport and support services: the latter has a 17 per cent weighting in the fund compared with 3 per cent in the FTSE All Share.\par \par \uc2 RPS, the environmental consultancy, at 2.8 per cent of his portfolio, is one of the biggest holdings. The Pounds 750m company, whose work includes advising on building projects, has improved its earnings by a compound annual rate of 25 per cent in the past decade, says Mr Watt.\par \par \uc2 But his top pick at the moment is First Group, the bus and train company that has just bought Laidlaw, the US owner of the Greyhound bus network. Mr Watt highlights the expected synergies between the two companies' school bus operations.\par \par \uc2 Among small caps, Mr Watt holds Tanfield, the electric van and lorry firm. He says that with Sainsbury's set to buy substantial numbers of electric vehicles, Tanfield "is the only player in town". \uc2 D1 Oils\uc2 , which grows and refines the biofuel crop jatropha, and which has just signed a joint venture with BP, is another favoured small stock.\par \par \uc2 Mr Watts is underweight in banks - not because of environmental issues, but because of concerns about interest rates.\par \par \uc2 Steve Lodge \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\cl