ard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PG\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 Page 2\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2007 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 At 10.30 this morning, Emma Newton will be among 72 people between the ages of 16 and 25 meeting for the first time at Reading Football Club. The 18-year-old business and administration student from Immingham will be taking part in a day of workshops, presentations, seminars and networking. But it won't be Reading's prospects for next season exercising her mind. Instead she and her colleagues will be receiving grants from a new joint private- and public-sector scheme to promote volunteering among young people. (The venue was chosen for its easy accessibility and youth-friendly sporting links.) Each of them has presented ideas for a new volunteering project and each will be going away with up to Pounds 2,500 towards making their plans a reality. \par \par \uc2 Newton's proposal, for which she has been given Pounds 2,500, is for a summer school for physically disabled and sensory-impaired children that begins at the end of the month in Grimsby. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "I was working already (as a volunteer) with older people," she says, "and I realised there was nothing available for younger people in my area. So I decided to put together a summer school for them." \par \par \uc2 The school, which will last five weeks and which goes under the imaginative name of "Eye Need Summer", will have "loads" of activities, she says, including ice-skating, samba dancing, drumming and karate, and she has already recruited 30-40 volunteers to run it, about half of whom are under 20. The Pounds 2,500, which goes straight into the project's bank account, will go towards venue hire, materials, volunteer expenses, such as travel, and fees for those tutors who can't be persuaded to give their time for free. \par \par \uc2 The charity responsible for handing out the money is V, set up by the government in May last year in response to a report by the Russell Commission's in 2005, which was set up the year before that by the then home secretary David Blunkett and Gordon Brown, then chancellor of the exchequer, to increase a sense of civic service among young people, for which volunteering would be a key part. V's aim is to attract 1m under-25s into volunteering and to this end it has a potential budget of Pounds 150m to give away between now and 2009. It has 30 staff based in central London and an annual budget of about Pounds 2m to cover administration costs. \par \par \uc2 "The traditional image of volunteering is associated with charity shops and things like that," says Terry Ryall, V's chief executive officer, who has a long track record in the voluntary and public sectors and who came to V from the Prince's Trust. "That's not inspiring a new generation. Young people are concerned about the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and similar issues and with family, friends, sport, music and so on. We want to bring all of that together." \par \par \uc2 V's aims, as well as the 1m target, are to improve the quality of volunteering opportunities in the UK and increase the diversity of people who volunteer. According to the Russell Commission, volunteering is seen as "uncool" by young people and many posts were simply unappealing. Home Office surveys and research by V itself have found that people from ethnic minorities and with disabilities are under-represented in the sector. The charity helps voluntary organisations organise and market themselves better and runs a website, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.vinspired.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.vinspired.com}}}\uc2  , where young people can find and apply for volunteer posts that appeal to them. \par \par \uc2 V's potential Pounds 150m budget comes from Pounds 50m it has to make direct grants and Pounds 50m available from the government to match, on a pound-for-pound basis, any private funding it can raise. (Working closely with the private sector was another of the Russell Commission's recommendations.) So far it has given about Pounds 15m to more than 100 organisations and has matched Pounds 7.5m of funding raised from companies such as T-Mobile, Tesco and KPMG. Among the organisations that have benefited from V grants this year are the Youth Sport Trust, People &Planet, a youth organisation that campaigns for the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and human rights, and the National Youth Theatre of Great Britain. \par \par \uc2 As well as providing grants directly to voluntary organisations, V has already engineered some significant public/private partnerships. For example, the youth charity Kickass and Barclays Bank are running a project to help young people with debt management. Today's event is the culmination of a partnership between another bank, \uc2 HSBC\uc2 , and V itself. \par \par \uc2 HSBC\uc2  has committed Pounds 500,000 over two years to V, which, when matched, becomes Pounds 1m of funding. It is working with the charity's "youth advisory board", a group of 20 people between 16 and 25 who advise V on its activities, assess applications for funding from other young people and work as roving ambassadors for the charity and for volunteering in general. \par \par \uc2 Some people might be sceptical about giving so much responsibility to some relatively young people but Ryall brushes aside doubts about today's youth. \par \par \uc2 "I have worked with young people for 30 years," she says, "and I have found the current generation as open to inspiration as any. With the right model and the right opportunities they can fly." \par \par \uc2 In fact Ryall's needs at the moment, she says, are not necessarily potential young volunteers - though she is a little coy when asked when the charity is likely to reach its 1m-volunteers target - but private-sector partners who can help release some more of the government's Pounds 50m. \par \par \uc2 "We have money available to match company's CSR (\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) projects that help young people and we have it available to 2009. What we are saying to corporate donors is, 'Come and get it,' and together we can get young people volunteering." \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile Newton is getting ready for her day in Reading. \par \par \uc2 "I began volunteering," she says, "because I wanted to do something to help out. I'm not bothered about getting paid. I'd rather put my time in and feel good about it. It doesn't matter how old or young you are. Volunteering's an opportunity for everyone." \par \par \uc2 V, tel: +44 (0)20-7960 7000 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.wearev.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.wearev.com}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.vinspired.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.vinspired.com}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20070721W102.065\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-1