\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (Copyright (c) 2007, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 For a country with an estimated 50 million poor people, Mexico appears to have its fair share of billionaires -- 10 according to Forbes's latest count -- many of whom head some of the country's biggest companies.\par \par \uc2 Although a number of the oldest businesses have a long tradition of giving back, it is only in recent years that the charitable activities of large and increasingly multinational corporations have been expanding and evolving.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Economic and corporate growth, escalating pressure from civil society and a change in business culture are encouraging companies to give more.\par \par \uc2 Recent efforts illustrate a transition from mere philanthropic donations to private-sector participation in the creation of development programs -- once the sole responsibility of the state -- built up around the latest buzz phrase: \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "Of course, a lot of this is just public relations and for tax purposes," says Barbara Merz of Harvard University's Global Equity Initiative. However, Ms. Merz believes, and others agree, that a change toward increased \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  also reflects a desire to expand the role of the private sector in social development. Well-targeted initiatives, some suggest, also assist financial performance.\par \par \uc2 Numbers are difficult to come by, but according to corporate foundations and academics studying the field, Mexican companies are continuing to give more, often in line with expanding revenue.\par \par \uc2 Fundacion Telmex is the social-assistance arm of Telefonos de Mexico, the fixed-line telephone company that dominates Mexico's telecommunications sector. The company is controlled by Carlos Slim, who is now said to have overtaken Bill Gates as the world's richest man.\par \par \uc2 Raul Ceron, a general coordinator of Fundacion Telmex, says the organization's educational, health, justice and cultural programs haven't changed in decades, but they have expanded alongside Telmex.\par \par \uc2 "Fortunately, we have the support of our entire corporate structure," he said in an interview. "We are a healthy company, with growth, and we have the economic capacity to help."\par \par \uc2 In 2006, Telmex had $16 billion in revenue and made an operating profit of $4.5 billion.\par \par \uc2 Wal-Mart de Mexico, the country's top retailer, also is widening its social-development efforts. It established a foundation as recently as 2003, and in 2006, it funneled more than $13 million to 181 nonprofit organizations, benefiting nearly 2 million people. The company recorded sales of $18.4 billion last year.\par \par \uc2 Grupo Televisa, Mexico's largest broadcaster, launched its foundation in February 2001, two months after Vicente Fox became the first president in 70 years who wasn't from the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.\par \par \uc2 Fundacion Televisa President Claudio Gonzalez describes Mr. Fox's election as a milestone in a decades-long weakening of the state's monopoly control over Mexican society.\par \par \uc2 "What I believe we are seeing now is an adjustment to a system of control where other actors begin to have a wider participation," Mr. Gonzalez says of the corporate sector's expanding social role. "It's a process, first of getting your footing, starting to grow and becoming more professional and efficient, and continuing to take sensible steps forward."\par \par \uc2 Fundacion Televisa has 24 employees, an annual budget of $8 million and a massive media infrastructure that it uses to develop alliances between the corporate sector, nongovernment organizations, civil society and government institutions.\par \par \uc2 Among its projects are a higher-education scholarship program funded by the company, members of the banking community, universities and state governments, as well as a project that has brought technology to 3,500 schools with the help of "redondeo" funds, where consumers can round up the amount of their purchases to the nearest peso and donate the difference to a development fund.\par \par \uc2 "Televisa puts forth the idea, 6 million pesos for the fund and the communications campaign," Mr. Gonzalez says. "This is the way in which we convert seed funding from the foundation into a major educational-technology or scholarship program."\par \par \uc2 The media company's efforts in this regard are an example of how the Mexican business community uses internal resources and private-sector efficiency to advance socially responsible activities.\par \par \uc2 Managers of corporate foundations insist their objective is helping the disadvantaged, but their efforts also assist the companies' image and bottom line.\par \par \uc2 "This is the only form through which all of this will become sustainable," says Gerardo Lozano, a philanthropy specialist at the Tecnologico de Monterrey university. "The companies' programs are aligned more and more with their strategies, trying to support the areas for which the company has an interest."\par \par \uc2 Effects of their activities on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and local communities also have led some companies to act.\par \par \uc2 Mining company Penoles, a big silver producer, is one example. In recent years, the firm has created community-development programs in its mining towns to assist those affected by its operations. Penoles conducted a major cleanup in the city of Torreon in 1999 after lead poisoning from its smelter was found among children living there.\par \par \uc2 The company, which has seen sales and profit soar on rising world commodities prices, said recently that it increased charitable spending by 70% in 2006 to $19 million.\par \par \uc2 The corporate responsibility efforts of Grupo Modelo, maker of Corona beer, center on an environmental program that includes conservation and reforestation.\par \par \uc2 "We, as a company, are conscious of the importance that the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  has, conscious that the majority of the raw materials we use comes from products that arise from the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," says Adolfo Alaniz, senior manager of the company's social-responsibility activities.\par \par \uc2 Fundacion Grupo Modelo also has education and other programs. "In addition to bringing benefits to the interested parties, we are somehow placing ourselves in a favorable situation of dialogue and exchange with our consumers," Mr. Alaniz says. "Tomorrow, this could turn into a competitive advantage."\par \par \uc2 Diana Chavez, who heads the Mexico branch of United Nations corporate-responsibility body The Global Compact, says \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  has become a major theme of Mexican business recently. "Today there exists a new consciousness," she says, noting similar trends elsewhere.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, the advancement of corporate responsibility in Mexico has a long way to go. Experts estimate that the percentages of corporate earnings given to social causes are significantly lower in Mexico than in developed countries with lower levels of poverty and inequality.\par \par \uc2 One place for improvement is through the participation of small and medium enterprises, for whom it is difficult to support their own foundation. Fundemex, an organization created in 2004, has begun to accumulate donations from small businesses and turn them into community-development programs.\par \par \uc2 Tecnologico de Monterrey's Mr. Lozano highlights another bottleneck: "Businesses want to involve themselves in social responsibility, but there still is a lack of developed talent for this inside the business community," he says.\par \par \uc2 Increased participation by wealthy families could also help. Mexican businesses are often inseparable from the families that control them, and local billionaires could follow the lead of Rockefellers, Carnegies and Gates to the north. Telmex owner Mr. Slim, who owns a number of Mexico's most-profitable enterprises, appears to be on such a course.\par \par \uc2 Aside from Fundacion Telmex, his efforts involve well-endowed Fundacion Carso and a partnership announced in June with the Clinton Foundation for a sustainable development initiative in Latin America.\par \par \uc2 Such efforts won't solve all of Mexico's problems, Harvard's Ms. Merz says, but they will help.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.d