the UK's most admired woman entrepreneur of recent years and will remain so for some time. \par \par \uc2 She continued to be cited as an inspiration by a younger generation of business founders long after the heyday of her Body Shop retail chain. This was in large part because she espoused \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  long before it was fashionable, showing that business success could be fuelled by personal convictions rather than hampered by them. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Dame Anita figured as a kind of female yin to the male yang of Sir Richard Branson in popular archetypes of entrepreneurship. Even today, many Britons would struggle to name any other entrepreneurs. \par \par \uc2 Her status reflected her personal image as deployed through the media and through advertising. She was happy to be the embodiment of her brand - principled, outspoken and opportunistic - in the same way that Sir Richard made himself and his Virgin empire synonymous with disrupting conventional business to the benefit of consumers. \par \par \uc2 Dame Anita was the daughter of Italian immigrants who, she said, "had a work ethic that teetered on the verge of slave labour". Writing in the Financial Times last year she recalled getting up at 5am to help make breakfast for local fishermen in the family cafe in Littlehampton. \par \par \uc2 She set up the first Body Shop in Brighton in 1976, at the tail end of hippy counter-culture in the UK. \par \par \uc2 However, the business's real expansionist glory days were in the 1980s when it was one of a gaggle of new retailers that also included fashion chain Next and narrowly focused outlets such as \uc2 Tie Rack\uc2  and \uc2 Sock Shop.\par \par \uc2 Body Shop was a counterpoise to the shoulder-padded wideboy chutzpah sometimes identified as the characteristic ethos of the 1980s. Its products were not tested on animals and customers were encouraged to re-use containers to for the sake of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2 The naturalness of ingredients was emphasised in product names. Dame Anita regarded herself as an "activist" rather than a businesswoman. She rued floating the company and viewed members of the quoted sector's professional management cadre with suspicion. \par \par \uc2 The distrust was mutual. The City was probably always more comfortable dealing with her husband, the rather less opinionated Gordon Roddick, who was latterly co-chairman of the business with his wife. \par \par \uc2 One critic recalls the Body Shop campaigning against European Union moves for compulsory testing of cosmetics on animals that appeared to exist only in the imagination of Body Shop executives. \par \par \uc2 Similarly, activists of the kind who limit themselves to criticising existing businesses rather than setting up new ones found fault with the ethics of Body Shop in recent years. The brand also lost some of its lustre because bigger retailers such as Boots had copied its back-to-nature philosophy. \par \par \uc2 None of this mattered in the least to fans of Dame Anita, who continued to look up to her as a woman who had succeeded in the male-dominated world of business on her own terms. \par \par \uc2 The UK has a troublingly low rate of start-ups led by women and a consequent shortage of role models for women entrepreneurs. Dame Anita was happy to fill that gap through speech-making, for example in support of Enterprise Week, theyearly government-backed push for business start-ups. \par \par \uc2 In her FT article ahead of that event last year, she wrote: "Entrepreneurs are outsiders. They are people who imagine things as they might be, not as they are, and have the drive to change the world. Those are qualities that business schools do not teach." \par \par \uc2 Of the viral infection that ultimately killed her, she said with a very 1960s insouciance that it was "a bit of a bummer".  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20070911L221.033\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 bdyshp : \uc2 Body Shop International plc | orl : \uc2 L'Oreal SA\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i64 : \uc2 Reta