 editor, interviewed Neville Isdell of \uc2 Coca Cola.\uc2  In this segment discussing the economy and protectionism. This is a transcript of the interview, which you may watch here. \par \par \uc2 Financial Times: Thank you for joining us, Mr Isdell. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Neville Isdell: It's a pleasure. \par \par \uc2 FT: Are you worried that the United States might be heading into a recession? \par \par \uc2 NI: I think we have to be concerned. I'm not predicting it. \par \par \uc2 FT: What is your prediction? \par \par \uc2 NI: I think we're in a difficult phase. Paulson spoke yesterday about this being more prolonged maybe, whether it's deeper or not than what happened with the Asian crisis and the Russian crisis etc, and I think that's true. No one quite understands the extent of it. The good news is the risk has been spread. The bad news is no one knows how much risk is there and how deep that is. Warren Buffett's wonderful phrase which is you don't know who's been swimming naked till the tide goes out. So, the tide is just going out and we don't really know the extent of that. I think we all have to be concerned that there can be an effect on global growth. \par \par \uc2 FT: Are you starting to see the impact of these more difficult times on the consumer? \par \par \uc2 NI: No. As I sit here today, we saw absolutely no impact at all. \par \par \uc2 FT: Has the credit crunch influenced your own view on share buy-backs? \par \par \uc2 NI: Not at this stage. We haven't re-evaluated that. It's something we look at continually. But we've got a very strong cash flow. Share buy-backs are really at the bottom of the ladder in terms of what we consider, because dividends obviously come first, and then it's acquisitions. Sorry, before that, I'm going in terms of priorities, and before that it's therefore investment in the business. So, really, it's what's left at the bottom of the bucket, as it were, and then you would use that for share buy-backs. We would be maybe as likely to inhibit our share buy-back because we've found a good acquisition as we were because of any credit crunch. \par \par \uc2 FT: And so you're not really conscious of an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  in which investors are requiring that companies have stronger balance sheets than they may have been thinking a year or two years ago? \par \par \uc2 NI: There's no question that in the broader context people are looking at companies have stronger balance sheets, but we've had a very strong balance sheet, that's the difference, and we've got a very strong cash flow. We spin off nearly $6.5bn of cash a year, and as we don't have a lot of fluctuations, we're really not at risk, whereas there are other people who are. But, clearly, there is a flight to quality. We believe we represent quality, that's part of it. Those who have stretched themselves more are going to have difficulty and banks, their lending is going to be crimped and certainly is going to be more discerning. \par \par \uc2 FT: Does the Fed need to cut rates? \par \par \uc2 NI: I'm not going to push the Fed one way or the other. I think they've got the data that I don't have, and you can't sit here and say, need to cut rates at the next available moment. I think the Fed has actually handled the economy very well over quite an extended period of time. I think they're on top of where things are now and they will respond appropriately. But I also think that the balance that they have is a very important balance because you've also got to have some moral hazard in here as well. \par \par \uc2 FT: Do you think those people who took unwise decisions need to be punished? \par \par \uc2 NI: Not punished, but I think people have to face up to their mistakes, and not always be rescued from their mistakes. Think of our own development, we learnt more from our mistakes than we did from some of our successes, and that, I think, is the nature of capitalism. And, if we underpin all the time people who over-stretch themselves and make basic, fundamental mistakes because they've tried to get too much of the pie too quickly. I think they deserve to suffer for that. \par \par \uc2 FT: Should we worry that protectionist sentiment is mounting, perhaps particularly in the United States? \par \par \uc2 NI: I wouldn't say just in the United States. I think it's a real concern. If we look at the global growth that we're experiencing at the moment, a lot of it goes back to the Uruguay round, a lot of it goes back to the formation of the WTO. It's the opening up of markets. I'm certainly worried about the Doha round. I've spoken about that on a number of occasions. I think if the Doha round does not prosper we're going to see that affecting global growth, there's no question. It's a development round. It's part of opening up part of the emerging markets. What I see in the debate is essentially a lack of economic literacy. People don't understand the laws of comparative advantage, and it's very easy to look at a job that's been lost and not see the other jobs that can be created by the opening up of trade. But, in the political debate in a number of countries we see economic populism coming into play. \par \par \uc2 FT: Where do you see the particular threats right now? \par \par \uc2 NI: I think the US is one of them, there is no question about it because there are three bilaterals, and I prefer multilaterals that's why Doha, I think, is so very important, but bilaterals are important too; four of them coming up before the Congress at the moment. They're all to the benefit of the US in terms of opening up trade, and yet most pundits say that it's going to be very difficult to get them through, and we certainly lend our voice to the passing of those. Plus, even internally, just on our website we put out something this week; educating our own employees because they're getting some of the feed about protecting jobs, and it always comes down to that. \par \par \uc2 FT: And so you're feeling that even within your own employee base? \par \par \uc2 NI: We've discovered that people don't really understand the argument of free trade and we're actually talking to our own people about it so they understand the importance of that. \par \par \uc2 FT: And that's here in the US specifically that you're doing this? \par \par \uc2 NI: In the US at the moment, but we'll roll it out everywhere because I think it's very important that people understand that. For us, a growing global economy is a growing company. It's in our shareholders' interests. But it's also in the interests of the world because what has taken more people out of poverty in the last 10 years? It's economic growth, and that's the opening up of markets and free trade, and if we could just get that simple message across to people, maybe, maybe we could get Doha through and we can go through another ramp-up of growth which will reduce poverty yet again by some pretty spectacular numbers, even in Africa. I was brought up in Africa. Even in Africa you see the growth coming through. It's taken time, but you've got to be relatively bullish on Africa right now. Not everywhere, but relatively bullish on Africa, and that's been the opening up of trade. \par \par \uc2 FT: Are business leaders doing enough to make that case, that public case for free trade? \par \par \uc2 NI: No, I don't think so. I think that what happened around Enron and the like, a lot of us put our heads below the parapet. I think we're now learning to bring our heads up above the parapet again, but I think, certainly on free trade, we need to be more outspoken. \par \par \uc2 FT: Thank you very much. \par \par \uc2 NI: Pleasure. \par \par \uc2 FT: And now Neville Isdell places his bets on long short. Okay, Mr Isdell, are you ready to play long short? \par \par \uc2 NI: I'm ready to play. \par \par \uc2 FT: The US dollar? \par \par \uc2 NI: Short. \par \par \uc2 FT: Healthy eating? \par \par \uc2 NI: Long. \par \par \uc2 FT: \uc2 Coca Cola\uc2  Blak? \par \par \uc2 NI: Short. \par \par \uc2 FT: Vladimir Putin? \par \par \uc2 NI: Long. \par \par \uc2 FT: US interest rate cut? \par \par \uc2 NI: I would go long on that. \par \par \uc2 FT: \uc2 Starbucks\uc2 ? \par \par \uc2 NI: Long. \par \par \uc2 FT: Gatorade? \par \par \uc2 NI: Short. \par \par \uc2 FT: Mandatory retirement? \par \par \uc2 NI: Short. If you interpret that the right way. I think that that is going to be removed eventually. \par \par \uc2 FT: War in Iraq? \par \par \uc2 NI: Short. \par \par \uc2 FT: Jean Claude Trichet? \par \par \uc2 N: Long. \par \par \uc2 FT: Thank you very much. That was Neville Isdell of \uc2 Coca Cola\uc2  on the economy and protectionism. You can also hear him discussing his board, acquisitions and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Next week, Subramanian Ramadorai of Tata reviews the news on video for FT.com's View From the Top.  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 58688476\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\f