e horses in Gordon Brown's "mainly political" speech, and spotted some welcome signals of future policy direction, particularly on climate change. \par \par \uc2 The prime minister's commitment to ensure green technologies were the "source of British jobs in British businesses" was applauded by industry last night. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "The idea that the UK could become a leader in green technologies is something we strongly believe and support," Richard Lambert, director-general of the CBI, told the FT. \par \par \uc2 The employers' body also backed Mr Brown's announcement that he will ask the new climate change committee to advise whether to change the UK's target of cutting carbon emissions by 60 per cent by 2050. \par \par \uc2 The issue is becoming increasingly politicised, with both main opposition parties advocating a higher target. Industry welcomed the promised review by an independent body. \par \par \uc2 Green groups also backed Mr Brown's aspiration for Britain to "lead in carbon-free vehicles, carbon-free homes and carbon-free industry." \par \par \uc2 Tony Juniper, executive director of Friends of the Earth, said it was "encouraging to see some emphasis on the domestic side . . . I'm also pleased to hear the opportunities (presented by climate change) coming from the prime minister". \par \par \uc2 It remains to be seen whether the prime minister can keep both industry and environmentalists happy, as he converts his green aspirations to concrete policies. Signs of the potential tensions were evident in the divergent reaction to Mr Brown's throwaway reference to his vision of the UK as a "world leader in energy and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , from nuclear to renewables." \par \par \uc2 Mr Juniper, whose organisation is implacably opposed to Britain building new nuclear power stations, highlighted the fact the government was still consulting on the issue. "I hope the prime minister has not jumped the gun," he said. But Mr Lambert stressed the CBI's support for the stance. \par \par \uc2 Business was relaxed about the reference to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the speech. Mr Brown's assertion that company boards have "the right . . . to make their own decisions, but obligations to the rest of society too" was seen as a political reaction to the recent Tory emphasis on this area, rather than a signal of looming new obligations. \par \par \uc2 But the speech as a whole was seen as having limited relevance to boardrooms. "It was mainly a political, even an election, speech," Mr Lambert said. "I think it was more aimed at the voters than either the business community or trades unions."  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20070925L102.136\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15