 oblivious" to the risks posed by climate change issues to their business models and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , according to a new study. \par \par \uc2 More than four out of 10 companies polled by CLSA, the broker, for its flagship regional survey of corporate governance, failed to answer any questions on green issues. Of the 582 companies surveyed, nearly two-thirds were given a zero score for their approach to climate change. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The findings, published yesterday, suggest Asian businesses badly lag behind their US and European rivals on this issue, which has risen to the top of the political agenda outside of the region. \par \par \uc2 The Financial Times reported yesterday that Wal-Mart is to ask its suppliers to measure and report their greenhouse gas emissions, on a day when world leaders debated climate change at the United Nations. \par \par \uc2 CLSA said it was "reckless" for companies to pay no attention to their environmental impact given mounting customer pressure, local enforcement and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2 Last year, 60 per cent of 150 Asian companies polled did not respond to a CLSA questionnaire on carbon management. \par \par \uc2 Amar Gill, CLSA head of thematic research, said: "The majority of Asian companies are not focused on this issue at all. They could soon be at a competitive disadvantage if they do not take steps to address the challenges." \par \par \uc2 Companies were invited to answer "yes" or "no" to 20 questions on climate change, including whether they had assigned individuals to lead a response to green issues and whether emission reduction targets had been set. \par \par \uc2 Indonesian companies posted the lowest response rate, of 22 per cent, to the section on climate change, followed by China (31 per cent) and Hong Kong (38 per cent). \par \par \uc2 Mr Gill said a common response among Hong Kong companies was they should not be subject to scrutiny on climate change because they did not produce emissions. \par \par \uc2 The report said: "Given China's rapid growth, driven by investments and industrial output . . . the lack of awareness to the climate change survey is alarming." \par \par \uc2 CLSA said it remained optimistic that companies in Asia would respond to calls for action to tackle climate change, as they had eventually done with persistent demands to improve corporate governance. \par \par \uc2 Researchers cited Asia's technology, materials and power and gas industries as the most attuned to climate change issues, as these were sectors that were globally "being brought to task". \par \par \uc2 The section on climate change formed part of a wider assessment of corporate governance in Asia, produced jointly with the Asian Corporate Governance Association, a lobby group for institutional investors.  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20070925L126.030\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph1