ar \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Socially responsible investing, typically a small corner of the fund world, is starting to attract mainstream attention in the US. \par \par \uc2 As concerns about topics such as climate change and human rights grow, SRI funds are a useful option for investors who do not want their savings invested in companies whose policies they disapprove of. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 This trend has seen assets in SRI mutual funds grow almost 50 per cent in less than four years, from $23.3bn (GBP11.2bn, 16.1bn) at the start of 2004 to $34.6bn as of September 30, according to figures from Lipper. \par \par \uc2 "There has been an explosion of interest," says Tim Smith, director of socially responsive investment at Walden Asset Management. \par \par \uc2 The growing interest in SRI is not just among individual investors. Institutional investors have also started to act on issues such as corporate governance and divestment (see Investors Against Genocide, right). \par \par \uc2 Denise Nappier, state treasurer and sole fiduciary of the $26bn Connecticut Retirement Plans and Trust (CPRT) Fund, is an activist shareholder whose efforts have, among other things, forced \uc2 American Electric Power\uc2  to report on how it is reducing its greenhouse emissions and pushed \uc2 Walt Disney\uc2  to split the job of chairman and chief executive. \par \par \uc2 Recently, CPRT sent a comment letter opposing the Securities and Exchange Commission's plans to strip shareholders of access to company proxies. The $256bn \uc2 California Public Employees' Retirement System\uc2  (Calpers) and the $86bn \uc2 State of Wisconsin Investment Board\uc2  also sent letters protesting the move. \par \par \uc2 Mr Smith believes corporate scandals, such as the Enron and WorldCom collapses in the early 2000s and the more recent problem of stock option backdating, have led to the growing interest in corporate governance and shareholder activism. "The investment community was often in the past a passive shareholder, but has today become a much more engaged shareowner," he says. \par \par \uc2 "The \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  agenda has never been more relevant," says Bennett Freeman, senior vice-president for social research and policy at Calvert, the largest SRI fund firm, with $8bn in SRI assets. Mr Freeman believes attitudes began to change in the mid-1990s, when sweatshop labour exploitation by US companies made headlines. At the same time oil companies were making news for the wrong reasons, best exemplified in 1995 by the criticism Shell received after the execution of Nigerian activist Ken Saro-Wiwa, who had been protesting against environmental damage caused by the oil industry. That year Shell also faced an outcry over its plans to dump the Brent Spar oil rig into the sea. Thiscombination of human rights and environmental worries is a feature of SRI concerns. \par \par \uc2 Mr Freeman, who was deputy assistant secretary of state for democracy, human rights and labour in the Clinton administration, believes that while attitudes at first changed to prevent the damaging publicity that these issues could bring, today companies are embracing SRI issues as part of their corporate strategy. \par \par \uc2 There are several examples of this newfound corporate focus on SRI. Unveiled in 2006, the UN-sponsored Principles for Responsible Investment established voluntary guidelines for both retail and institutional investors, focused on environmental, social and corporate governance issues. \par \par \uc2 The Principles document has almost 250 signatories, including Calpers, CPRT and state pension plans from New York and Illinois. \uc2 JPMorgan\uc2  Asset Management, \uc2 ABN Amro Asset Management\uc2  and \uc2 Axa Investment Managers\uc2  are among the investment managers that have signed up. Total assets of the signatories are about $10,000bn. Meanwhile, the Carbon Disclosure Project, founded in 2000, now receives reports from 2,400 companies, data that is passed to institutional investors that have more than $41,000bn in assets. \par \par \uc2 "It's become a business opportunity and companies are connecting sustainability and social responsibility to their corporate strategy," Mr Freeman says. This has created an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  where SRI investors can thrive. "The challengefor SRI funds is to become asmainstream as \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he adds. \par \par \uc2 That challenge is in part to define SRI as a positive concept that can attract investors rather than simply a vehicle to avoid certain types of investments. \par \par \uc2 While the early SRI funds in the 1970s and 1980s were defined by what they would not invest in - alcohol, tobacco and gambling were three standard no-gos - today SRI funds are actively seeking companies that have policies they can embrace. \par \par \uc2 Funds now screen for companies that have made efforts in the areas of labour rights, human rights, workplace diversity, corporate governance and ethics, environmental and climate change and community efforts. \par \par \uc2 This type of screening can yield surprising names, with Walden's Mr Smith highlighting IBMfor its positive approach todiversity, while Mr Freeman names BP and Shell for their effortsin the renewable energies area. But there is more to SRI than corporate issues. Morningstar estimates that of the 100 or so SRI mutual funds in the US, about 40 invest on a religious basis. Some of the better known, such as the Ave Maria Mutual Funds, screen based on explicitly social issues, shunning hospitals and drug companies that it connects with abortions. Another screen Ave Maria uses excludes companies that provide benefits for the non-married partners of employees. \par \par \uc2 This leads to some investments that would not normally be thought of as the province of an SRI fund - Halliburton, \uc2 Exxon Mobil\uc2  and defence contractor \uc2 General Dynamics\uc2 , for example. \par \par \uc2 SRI funds also keep pace with the performance of other funds. Lipper data shows that year-to-date, SRI funds have returned 11.66 per cent compared to the fund industry average of 11.27 per cent. Leading the way is the Amana Growth Fund, an Islamic-based religious fund. The fund is rated five-star by Morningstar. \par \par \uc2 What marks the fund out from other SRIs is that it avoids, in accordance with the Koran's proscription on usury, financial services companies and all interest paying instruments, including bonds. \par \par \uc2 Sam Mamudi is managing editor of the Fund Action newsletter  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\as