\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Socially responsible investing, typically a small corner of the fund world, is starting to attract mainstream attention in the US.\par \par \uc2 As concerns about topics such as climate change and human rights grow, SRI funds are a useful option for investors who do not want their savings invested in companies whose policies they disapprove of.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 This trend has seen assets in SRI mutual funds grow almost 50 per cent in less than four years, from Dollars 23.3bn (Pounds 11.2bn, Euros 16.1bn) at the start of 2004 to Dollars 34.6bn as of September 30, according to figures from Lipper.\par \par \uc2 "There has been an explosion of interest," says Tim Smith, director of socially responsive investment at Walden Asset Management.\par \par \uc2 The growing interest in SRI is not just among individual investors.\par \par \uc2 Institutional investors have also started to act on issues such as corporate governance and divestment (see Investors Against Genocide, right).\par \par \uc2 Denise Nappier, state treasurer and sole fiduciary of the Dollars 26bn Connecticut Retirement Plans and Trust (CPRT) Fund, is an activist shareholder whose efforts have, among other things, forced \uc2 American Electric Power\uc2  to report on how it is reducing its greenhouse emissions and pushed \uc2 Walt Disney\uc2  to split the job of chairman and chief executive.\par \par \uc2 Recently, CPRT sent a comment letter opposing the Securities and Exchange Commission's plans to strip shareholders of access to company proxies. The Dollars 256bn \uc2 California Public Employees' Retirement System\uc2  (Calpers) and the Dollars 86bn \uc2 State of Wisconsin Investment Board\uc2  also sent letters protesting the move.\par \par \uc2 Mr Smith believes corporate scandals, such as the Enron and WorldCom collapses in the early 2000s and the more recent problem of stock option backdating, have led to the growing interest in corporate governance and shareholder activism. "The investment community was often in the past a passive shareholder, but has today become a much more engaged shareowner," he says.\par \par \uc2 "The \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  agenda has never been more relevant," says Bennett Freeman, senior vice-president for social research and policy at Calvert, the largest SRI fund firm, with Dollars 8bn in SRI assets. Mr Freeman believes attitudes began to change in the mid-1990s, when sweatshop labour exploitation by US companies made headlines. At the same time oil companies were making news for the wrong reasons, best exemplified in 1995 by the criticism Shell received after the execution of Nigerian activist Ken Saro- Wiwa, who had been protesting against environmental damage caused by the oil industry. That year Shell also faced an outcry over its plans to dump the Brent Spar oil rig into the sea. This combination of human rights and environmental worries is a feature of SRI concerns.\par \par \uc2 Mr Freeman, who was deputy assistant secretary of state for democracy, human rights and labour in the Clinton administration, believes that while attitudes at first changed to prevent the damaging publicity that these issues could bring, today companies are embracing SRI issues as part of their corporate strategy.\par \par \uc2 There are several examples of this newfound corporate focus on SRI. Unveiled in 2006, the UNsponsored Principles for Responsible Investment established voluntary guidelines for both retail and institutional investors, focused on environmental, social and corporate governance issues.\par \par \uc2 The Principles document has almost 250 signatories, including Calpers, CPRT and state pension plans from New York and Illinois.\par \par \uc2 JPMorgan\uc2  Asset Management, \uc2 ABN Amro Asset Management\uc2  and \uc2 Axa Investment Managers\uc2  are among the investment managers that have signed up. Total assets of the signatories are about Dollars 10,000bn.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the Carbon Disclosure Project, founded in 2000, now receives reports from 2,400 companies, data that is passed to institutional investors that have more than Dollars 41,000bn in assets.\par \par \uc2 "It's become a business opportunity and companies are connecting sustainability and social responsibility to their corporate strategy," Mr Freeman says. This has created an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  where SRI investors can thrive. "The challenge for SRI funds is to become as mainstream as \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he adds.\par \par \uc2 That challenge is in part to define SRI as a positive concept that can attract investors rather than simply a vehicle to avoid certain types of investments.\par \par \uc2 While the early SRI funds in the 1970s and 1980s were defined by what they would not invest in - alcohol, tobacco and gambling were three standard no-gos - today SRI funds are actively seeking companies that have policies they can embrace.\par \par \uc2 Funds now screen for companies that have made efforts in the areas of labour rights, human rights, workplace diversity, corporate governance and ethics, environmental and climate change and community efforts.\par \par \uc2 This type of screening can yield surprising names, with Walden's Mr Smith highlighting IBM for its positive approach to diversity, while Mr Freeman names BP and Shell for their efforts in the renewable energies area.\par \par \uc2 But there is more to SRI than corporate issues. Morningstar estimates that of the 100 or so SRI mutual funds in the US, about 40 invest on a religious basis. Some of the better known, such as the Ave Maria Mutual Funds, screen based on explicitly social issues, shunning hospitals and drug companies that it connects with abortions.\par \par \uc2 Another screen Ave Maria uses excludes companies that provide benefits for the non-married partners of employees.\par \par \uc2 This leads to some investments that would not normal ly be thought of as the province of an SRI fund - Halliburton, \uc2 Exxon Mobil\uc2  and defence contractor \uc2 General Dynamics\uc2 , for example.\par \par \uc2 SRI funds also keep pace with the performance of other funds.\par \par \uc2 Lipper data shows that year-todate, SRI funds have returned 11.66 per cent compared to the fund industry average of 11.27 per cent.\par \par \uc2 Leading the way is the Amana Growth Fund, an Islamic-based religious fund. The fund is rated five-star by Morningstar.\par \par \uc2 What marks the fund out from other SRIs is that it avoids, in accordance with the Koran's proscription on usury, financial services companies and all interest paying instruments, including bonds.\par \par \uc2 Sam Mamudi is managing editor of the Fund Action newsletter\par \par \uc2 Investors Against Genocide\par \par \uc2 The most highprofile area of the SRI world is the campaign to divest from Sudan. Activists protesting about the humanitarian crisis in Darfur have targeted money managers who invest in oil companies, among them \uc2 PetroChina\uc2 , that work with the Sudanese government. Eric Cohen, chairperson of Investors Against Genocide, an organisation launched in September by the founders of the Fidelity Out of Sudan campaign, says that targeted divestment is the activists' preferred approach after the economic campaigns against apartheidera South Africa proved to be a "very blunt instrument." That campaign led to many black South Africans losing their jobs as economic sanctions hit.\par \par \uc2 The scale of the Darfur crisis is also one that most investors can appreciate. "SRI may mean different things to different people, but there is a basic minimum principle," says Mr Cohen. "No one wants to be connected to genocide." \uc2 Fidelity Investments\uc2  was targeted because it was the largest holder on the New York Stock Exchange of \uc2 PetroChina\uc2  stock.\par \par \uc2 Twenty US states have decided to divest from companies linked to Sudan since June 2005, 14 of them this year. Seventeen of the states have passed divestment laws. Fiftythree colleges have also divested, including Harvard University, manager of Dollars 35bn (Pounds 17bn, Euros 24bn).\par \par \uc2 Among investment companies the response has been less positive and even the successes have been muddied. After \uc2 Berkshire Hathaway\uc2  cashed out of \uc2 PetroChina\uc2  in midOctober, Warren Buffett denied the selloff had anything to do with Darfur, telling Fox News Business that he made Dollars 3.5bn on a Dollars 500m investment and that with hindsight he felt he sold too soon.\par \par \uc2 And while an August filing showed that Fidelity had sold 99 per cent of its American Depositary Receipts in \uc2 PetroChina\uc2 , Vin Loporchio, a Fidelity spokesman, says the firm did not instruct the sales. "Each portfolio manager makes decisions based on his or her assessment of a stock's value," he says. Mr Loporchio would not comment on whether the managers decided to sell for reasons relating to the divestment campaign.\par \par \uc2 He adds that Fidelity offers funds for SRIseeking investors.\par \par \uc2 Other investment firms identified by Mr Cohen's group, including Franklin Templeton, Pimco parent \uc2 Allianz\uc2  and Vanguard have retained their \uc2 PetroChina\uc2  stakes. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  