the past few years as growing concerns over problems such as climate change, pollution in developing countries, and the loss of biodiversity have prompted consumers, governments and businesses to start finding solutions. \par \par \uc2 Tom Woollard, a veteran consultant and business development director at Environmental Resources Management, has seen it all before. He points to previous waves of interest in green issues, in the 1970s, 1980s and 1990s. But this one, he thinks, is here to stay. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 He explains: "This is much bigger. More people are aware of the importance of these problems. We are coming to the point with issues such as climate change that now it is no longer an option whether to do something about it. It is now a must." \par \par \uc2 Most companies in the FTSE 100 - and an increasing number around the world - now report on their carbon emissions, though they are not obliged to. \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  wants its suppliers to start disclosing their carbon emissions. Companies such as \uc2 Coca-Cola\uc2  and \uc2 Cadbury Schweppes\uc2  are taking steps towards labelling their products based on how much carbon went into their production. A few companies, including \uc2 HSBC\uc2 , \uc2 News Corporation\uc2 , \uc2 Dell Computer\uc2 , \uc2 British Sky Broadcasting\uc2  and \uc2 Marks and Spencer\uc2 , are even going "carbon neutral". \par \par \uc2 Governments around the world are toughening environmental regulations. The US is considering a federal regulation that would cap companies' carbon output and allow them to trade in permits to emit carbon, along the lines of the system in the European Union. Waste is also increasingly regulated, as is the use of potentially harmful materials. \par \par \uc2 With so much corporate and regulatory activity concentrated on making companies greener, the market for environmental consultancy has expanded substantially. Quite how much is difficult to say, because of differing definitions of environmental work. In the UK its growth is estimated by Environmental Data Services at nearly 20 per cent a year. The sector in the UK has been estimated at Pounds 1.5bn a year. \par \par \uc2 Environmental consultanices range from one-person firms advising companies on energy efficiency or waste management, to units of large engineering groups. The Big Four and smaller management consultancies also now boast inhouse environmental specialisms. For instance, KPMG has a "carbon advisory group" helping companies tackle their impacts on climate change. It also helped Ecotricity, a renewable energy company, raise finance to build wind farms. Booz Allen Hamilton has developed a way to measure the "carbon footprint" of a company's supply chain, and has refurbished its Savoy Court offices to high standards of efficiency. \par \par \uc2 Deloitte says its activities have included advising investors in areas such as renewable energy; helping organisations to procure waste management services; auditing \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  reports; providing services to financial institutions that may have exposure to liabilities resulting from climate change; and advising the UK government on policy options on greenhouse gas reduction. \par \par \uc2 Charles Gooderham of Deloitte says: "We help clients respond to these challenges through blending \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  expertise with business advisory skills. Clients benefit from sound commercial advice underpinned by a detailed knowledge of the underlying environmental drivers." \par \par \uc2 He says companies should see environmental issues as a core part of their business strategy, not an optional extra: "The best way of sustaining a paradigm shift in corporate behaviour is by making it integral to business strategy and shareholder value." \par \par \uc2 Carmel McQuaid, a senior consultant on sustainability at \uc2 PA Consulting\uc2 , says businesses want to prepare for tougher regulation: "Clients are increasingly seeking guidance and support on how to transform their business to thrive in a carbon constrained world. Management consultancies play a vital role in that, be it quantification and reduction of carbon footprints, developing more next-generation sustainable products and packaging, or enabling public sector projects to set leadership examples." \par \par \uc2 Consultants are also keen to develop their skills in a specialism that is rapidly expanding, and which interests and motivates people at a personal as well as an intellectual level. For younger people in particular, it is increasingly important to feel that their company is not damaging the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Mr Gooderham reports: "Both the opportunity to work on \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  related projects, and the environmental performance of Deloitte, are seen as important factors by the younger generation of employees." \par \par \uc2 But the environmental performance of management consultancies is itself a tricky area. Consultancies are working to cut their "carbon footprint" - witness AT Kearney's decision to be "carbon neutral" within two years. \par \par \uc2 Achieving a lower environmental impact can be hard. Ms McQuaid notes: "Some could argue that management consultancy is not a sustainable business model due to the large footprint associated with business travel. In a carbon-constrained world, do we really want to have professions that rely on flying their people around the world?" \par \par \uc2 PA Consulting\uc2  says staff regularly ask questions about the company's environmental impact, and, increasingly, clients are also asking for evidence of the company's commitment to cutting its impact when procuring services. \par \par \uc2 Ultimately, companies may find consulting on environmental issues is not so different from advising on general corporate productivity issues. Andy Mulholland, chief technology officer at \uc2 Capgemini\uc2 , which helps companies find ways to cut the "carbon footprint" of their computer operations, says: "The \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  issue is nothing more than a question of common sense - much of the task is simply good business practice."  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20071119S108.225\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 cbry : \uc2 Cadbury plc | pcltd : \uc2 Dell Inc | hksbc : \uc2 HSBC Holdings PLC | coca : \uc2 The Coca-Cola Company | bzalnh : \uc2 Booz Allen Hamilton Holding Corp. | krnyat : \uc2 A.T. Kearney Inc | wlmrt : \uc2 Wal-Mart S