ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2008 Dow Jones & Company, Inc. To see the edition in which this article appeared, click here   \uc2 http://awsj.com.hk/factiva-ns\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 IN ONE OF THE most widely watched efforts in corporate philanthropy in years,  \uc2 Google Inc.\uc2  said it will dole out nearly $30 million in new grants and investments to nonprofits and a private business that are taking on do-good projects such as tapping solar power, preventing plagues and improving public services for the poor.   \par \par \uc2 Google\uc2 's push into philanthropy is being watched closely because of its size and its effort to erase the usual boundaries between the for-profit and nonprofit worlds.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Valued around $2 billion, the assets currently set aside for the company's philanthropic arm,  \uc2 Google.org\uc2 , make it larger than any other in-house corporate foundation in the U.S., according to the Foundation Center, a nonprofit research firm. (Private foundations set up by tycoons such  \uc2 Microsoft Corp.\uc2 's Bill Gates have more assets.)   \par \par \uc2 Just as important, the Mountain View, California, Internet company is marshalling both company and foundation resources around the initiatives, which it hopes will provide more impact in tackling some of the world's biggest problems. Philanthropy experts consider  \uc2 Google\uc2  to be among the leading edge of donors who are experimenting with this hybrid for-profit/nonprofit model. Others include  \uc2 eBay Inc.\uc2  founder Pierre Omidyar's Omidyar Network, which both invests in businesses and makes grants to nonprofits.   \par \par \uc2 Google\uc2  says it isn't looking to make money on its philanthropic efforts. But, as a division of the for-profit company rather than a nonprofit offshoot,  \uc2 Google.org\uc2  has freedom to invest in and operate businesses, lobby for political causes and issue certain types of grants that a traditional corporate foundation wouldn't. Its announcement Thursday includes a $10 million investment in closely held eSolar Inc., which is working on utility-scale solar power.  \uc2 Google.org\uc2  also expects to invest directly in businesses in places such as Africa to spur job creation. "We can start new industries," says Executive Director Larry Brilliant. "I hope we will."   \par \par \uc2 Thursday,  \uc2 Google.org\uc2  unveiled the first set of major five- to eight-year initiatives it will pursue. The initiatives include efforts to create systems for helping predict and prevent disease pandemics, to empower the poor with information about their public services and to spur job creation by facilitating investment in developing-world small and midsize businesses.   \par \par \uc2 They join previously announced initiatives to accelerate the commercialization of plug-in cars and make renewable energy cheaper than coal.  \uc2 Google\uc2  will work with partners in each area, although it plans to directly invest money in businesses and operate some of the projects itself.   \par \par \uc2 The money  \uc2 Google.org\uc2  has awarded to date remains modest, and its progress so far has been slow compared with its parent company's breakneck growth in staff and business reach. Some philanthropy experts warn  \uc2 Google\uc2  that successful businesspeople with high hopes for solving the world's problems have underestimated those problems' complexity and fallen short before.   \par \par \uc2 But, coming nearly four years after  \uc2 Google\uc2  first announced it was devoting 1% of its equity, 1% of profits annually and an unspecified amount of employee time to  \uc2 Google.org\uc2 , Thursday's announcement gives much-awaited shape and focus to its activities.   \par \par \uc2 Selected from among over 800 suggestions, the final initiatives show  \uc2 Google\uc2 's special interest in projects where it can bring its engineering and information-management prowess to bear.  \uc2 Google\uc2  staff, many of whom enjoy freedom to spend 20% of their time on independent projects, are expected to contribute significantly to  \uc2 Google.org\uc2  efforts. The winning initiatives also exhibit  \uc2 Google\uc2 's characteristic penchant for audacious moves to reshape markets -- from advertising to developing-world small-business financing -- others are often more timid in approaching.   \par \par \uc2 Google.org\uc2 's big ambitions suggest that it could potentially transform the business mix of  \uc2 Google\uc2  itself -- leading the company to become a player in sectors such as energy and finance.   \par \par \uc2 "They're business and technology people saying we want to find business and technology solutions to problems," says Mark Kramer, Managing Director of FSG Social Impact Advisors, a nonprofit philanthropy and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social\b0 \highlight\uc2 -\b \highlight22\uc2 responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  consulting and research group. "That hasn't been done much before."   \par \par \uc2 The roots of the effort trace back to  \uc2 Google\uc2 's April 2004 regulatory filing for an initial public offering. In it, company co-founders Sergey Brin and Larry Page announced plans for a corporate foundation with the goal that "someday this institution may eclipse  \uc2 Google\uc2  itself in terms of overall world impact by ambitiously applying innovation and significant resources to the largest of the world's problems."   \par \par \uc2 To get started, the company created a nonprofit corporate foundation with about $90 million in funding. It announced plans to focus on issues related to energy and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and global poverty.   \par \par \uc2 After discovering in 2005 that its foundation couldn't easily donate to the One Laptop Per Child project, a nonprofit initiative to sell low-cost laptops to developing countries,  \uc2 Google\uc2  began pursuing the hybrid approach with the for-profit structure. Laws prevent corporate foundations from making gifts that might financially benefit their businesses, and the laptop project aimed at increasing Internet access arguably could boost  \uc2 Google\uc2 's online advertising revenue.   \par \par \uc2 In February 2006,  \uc2 Google\uc2  hired as  \uc2 Google.org\uc2 's executive director Dr. Brilliant, a colorful former physician who helped direct efforts to eradicate smallpox from India in the 1970s, and after the Sept. 11 attacks, served as a bioterrorism consultant to the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.   \par \par \uc2 With Dr. Brilliant's arrival,  \uc2 Google.org\uc2  added global health as a third focus area. He and colleagues sought advice from leaders in the philanthropy field and  \uc2 Google\uc2  staff and made small "learning grants" to nonprofits. But by spring 2007, Dr. Brilliant and his team realized they needed to focus on a limited set of initiatives in the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , poverty and global health areas.   \par \par \uc2 In June, they kicked off an internal competition to select the top initiatives. As part of the competition presentations, internal teams had to outline how the initiatives were pro-poor, how they would measure success, how they would take advantage of  \uc2 Google\uc2 's resources and what their potential impact was.   \par \par \uc2 The company is testing a system to create ways to measure the success of the initiatives and plans eventually to disclose to the public data about the performance of  \uc2 Google.org\uc2 's efforts.   \par \par \uc2 Some philanthropy experts say it is too early to predict how successful  \uc2 Google.org\uc2  will be, and how effective a hybrid nonprofit/for-profit approach will prove.   \par \par \uc2 Bruce Sievers, Visiting Scholar at the Haas Center for Public Service at Stanford University, says his qualm about high-tech money backing such efforts generally is "just the whole thing of hubris." Such funders often believe, he adds: "'We have a lot of smarts and a lot of money; we're going to weigh in in these social situations.' And they're so unbelievably complex." Mr. Sievers, former executive director of the Walter and Elise Haas Fund, says it remains to be seen whether such concerns apply to  \uc2 Google.org.\par \par \uc2 For their part, Dr. Brilliant's colleagues acknowledge the effort has been daunting. "Is solving world poverty or changing the course of climate change harder than running an advertising business, even if it's  \uc2 Google\uc2 ?" asks Google Vice President Sheryl Sandberg, who sits on  \uc2 Google.org\uc2 's board. "Yes," she says.   \par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.djreprints.com/link/DJRFactiva.html?FACTIVA=waco20080117000094"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 License this article from Dow Jones Reprint Service}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 goog : \uc2 Google Inc.\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i8395464 : \uc2 Internet Search Engines | iint : \uc2 Internet/Online Services\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | gpov : \uc2 Poverty | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gcom : \uc2 Society/Community/Work | gsoc : \uc2 