palpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Andrew Edgecliffe-Johnson\par \par \uc2 Media editor\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 It was hard to escape the sense that the business leaders who had been chauffeured and helicoptered into Davos to talk about what they were doing to improve the world felt a little upstaged.\par \par \uc2 The Federal Reserve's sharp rate cut on the eve of the World Economic Forum and the revelation of a massive fraud at Societe Generale two days later ensured that discussions were dominated by debates about economic and market turmoil.\par \par \uc2 "The meeting and the mood today has been overshadowed by the financial crisis," Indra Nooyi, chief executive of \uc2 PepsiCo\uc2 , admitted on day one, reminding other delegates that they were at Davos to address long-term challenges rather than shortterm issues.\par \par \uc2 Yet as the week went on, the corporate leaders' messages began to cut through. One of those messages was that they were less convinced than the economists and bankers that the outlook is entirely gloomy.\par \par \uc2 Sony\uc2 's experience runs counter to "the aroma of disaster wafting through the halls of Davos", said Sir Howard Stringer, chairman of the Japanese electronics and media group.\par \par \uc2 Niall FitzGerald, chairman of Reuters, the news and financial information group, noted that the mood was less bearish the further east an executive was from Frankfurt. Any fears among American delegates contrasted with optimism from Russian, Chinese or Indian companies.\par \par \uc2 The other overriding business theme was, again, \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . But after last year's parties in a "climate change igloo" there was less public relations glitz and more of a recognition that companies' responses to environmental issues will affect their bottom line.\par \par \uc2 Customers now expect companies to have meaningful environmental policies, one senior advertising executive said, adding that publicity stunts no longer impressed. "Brands will have a really tough time in this \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , unless they have a genuine role, over and above the services they provide," Mr FitzGerald added.\par \par \uc2 Perhaps as a result, executives from companies as diverse as \uc2 Coca-Cola\uc2 , \uc2 Nestle\uc2  and \uc2 Dow Chemical\uc2  rallied around a central theme of this year's Forum: the growing scarcity of resources, from clean water to affordable food to accessible oil.\par \par \uc2 All are inter-related, they said, and each has a role to play in climate change, the dominant theme of Davos last year. That overarching but somewhat intangible challenge is now comprehensible to business in terms of key ingredients in the corporate supply chain.\par \par \uc2 As they announced their own initiatives or pledged to rally round the UN's Millennium Development Goals, the corporate mood was again summed up by Ms Nooyi at the end of the week.\par \par \uc2 Issuing a challenge to her fellow CEOs, she said: "It is time to move from discussion to decision."\par \par \uc2 Chris Giles\par \par \uc2 Economics editor\par \par \uc2 The mood of Davos in the economics sphere was one of grim determination. Grim because the people who should know are most sure the credit market crisis stalking the world is far from over. Determination because financial company leaders, central bankers and finance ministers are focused on doing what is needed to sort out the mess.\par \par \uc2 But there is a problem. No one is entirely sure how bad it is or what is required. And with uncertainty comes disagreement.\par \par \uc2 Central bankers have a terrible trade-off tomake when thinking about the right level of interest rates. In such uncertain times, they all concede the risk of mistakes is high. But there is a big difference between central bankers on each side of the Atlantic, which is not solely explained by the severity of the problems they face.\par \par \uc2 In the US, the Fed cut interest rates by 0.75 percentage points on the day most delegates arrived in Davos. The Fed's move reflected a desire to do what was necessary to avoid a vicious circle of financial crisis, recession and further bad loans.\par \par \uc2 If the Fed went too far, it was because, with its risk management approach to monetary policy, it viewed the risks of a vicious credit cycle as outweighing the dangers of moral hazard in financial markets and rising public expectations of inflation.\par \par \uc2 In numerous on- and off-the-record sessions, US policymakers, past and present, stressed the need to do almost anything to avoid the downturn becoming worse.\par \par \uc2 European policymakers, by contrast, are more nervous about defending their hard-won credibility as inflation fighters. Publicly and privately they stress the need for the private sector to reprice risk and, though they stand ready to act to offset recessionary forces, they believe that credibility against inflation is hard to gain but easy to lose.\par \par \uc2 While these debates were raging at Davos, right at the end of the forum, Dominique Strauss-Kahn, the new managing director of the International Monetary Fund, dropped a bombshell into the mix.\par \par \uc2 He urged governments to relax fiscal policy to avoid a deeper downturn. It was as unexpected as it was dramatic.\par \par \uc2 Fiscal policy as a tool for demand management has been low on the IMF's list of preferred policies for decades because its record is poor. The action is often mistimed and hard to reverse. With this history, his call for fiscal stimulus shows just how bad the IMF thinks the situation could get.\par \par \uc2 More importantly, it reflects a loss of hope that China and oil producers will play their part inreducing global imbalances by boosting domestic consumption as the US and other economies slow.\par \par \uc2 The IMF's new calculation is, therefore, that preserving global imbalances with rich country fiscal deficits is better than a nasty unwinding starting with a US recession. But that, of course, raises the question of how global imbalances will ever be reduced.\par \par \uc2 Gillian Tett\par \par \uc2 Global markets editor\par \par \uc2 When the delegates gathered in Davos last year, the mood was marked by genteel good cheer. Almost every debate started with an acknowledgement that the economic outlook seemed benign.\par \par \uc2 Thus, for a journalist who was hunting for a story, the gathering seemed almost disappointingly staid. Indeed, the only moment I heard drama was when a fiery debate erupted at a lunch to discuss whether or not derivatives were beneficial for the global financial system.\par \par \uc2 What a difference 12 months makes. This year's gathering was replete with endless debate, both in public and private, about financial turmoil. Meanwhile, discussions about derivatives were no longer relegated to distant hotels for a specialist lunch.\par \par \uc2 Instead, the speeches in the main conference hall were studded with rhetoric about once-esoteric topics such as collateralised debt obligations and the state of structured finance.\par \par \uc2 On one level, this might seem reassuring - at least for those who believe that Davos is a wonderfully good counter-cyclical indicator. The tone of these debates about financial stability was markedly bleak: most observers agreed that there is more bad credit news to come, and levels of trust in the financial system are low.\par \par \uc2 But this suggests that policymakers now recognise the scale of the problems - which might also imply that the credit squeeze is finally about to turn. Or, as one senior banker said: "Davos has a habit of reinforcing whatever the elite think. If everybody agrees things will get worse, we may be near a bottom." But whether this prediction is true or not - and, personally, I still regard this as a bold bet - what was also clear from this year's meeting is that pressure is building on this elite to change the way it oversees global finance.\par \par \uc2 One of the most striking moments of the entire forum was a poll conducted by CNBC which showed that 59 per cent of delegates feared that financial authorities, such as central banks, had lost control of events in recent months. Given that the halls of Davos are peopled by many of these very same financial policymakers, it is a fair bet that a poll taken outside the Swiss resort would display even higher levels of alarm.\par \par \uc2 The upshot? This year's Davos crowd now has a huge and urgent task ahead of it to restore real confidence into modern finance. And judging from the debates, I would guess that there is still little consensus about how to implement this crucial task. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20080205S105.973\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-1