rcial property on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  is to be launched next week by a group of the sector's leading organisations and corporate occupiers. \par \par \uc2 The so-called "\b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  code", which has the support of bodies such as the CBI, the employers' organisation, and Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors (Rics), as well as companies such as \uc2 Barclays\uc2  and BP, aims to provide a single international benchmark to assess the impact of buildings on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Corporate property is estimated to be responsible for some 20 per cent of global CO 2 emissions, mainly via energy use, but also through waste and water production. About 50 per cent of a company's CO 2 emissions are said to be produced by its real estate, making it a key target for tackling pollution under many \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  programmes. \par \par \uc2 "Analysis carried out for the CBI Task Force on Climate Change showed that buildings represent one of the largest areas of potential to cut UK carbon emissions," said Richard Lambert, CBI director-general. "The code will facilitate more informed decisions about which buildings to occupy and how to manage the operations that take place within them." \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  code aims to go further than just addressing energy efficiency, which is already being assessed by the government, by providing an internationally recognised system for companies with offices around the world. \par \par \uc2 The code, to be launched next Tuesday at City Hall in London, has been formulated by the \uc2 Investment Property Databank\uc2 , which provides the benchmark for valuations in the industry, alongside \uc2 CB Richard Ellis\uc2 , international real estate adviser, and \uc2 Bureau Veritas\uc2 , the business consultant. \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  code will provide a relatively simple template for the collection, measurement and analysis of environmental information from real estate. It is designed to work alongside local building regulations, but be applicable anywhere in the world so corporate occupiers can assess their global environmental impact. \par \par \uc2 Companies could not add-ress their environmental impact unless they could accurately measure it, said Christopher Hedley, IPD director. He predicted that a standardised system would have an impact on the value of buildings, where the more polluting would be able to command less rent and so would be worth less owing to their lack of a decent environmental rating. \par \par \uc2 "We already have quite a few corporate clients who only go into certain buildings that are environmentally responsible," said \par \par \uc2 Mr Hedley.  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20080222L104.492\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \t