 A group of pioneers in the ''green business'' were getting back to their roots with a two-day hike through a pristine rain forest in Costa Rica when they hit Fer-de-lance Hill.    \par \par \uc2 ''Dare I ask why this hill is called Fer-de-lance Hill?'' one hiker, Tom Newmark, had asked another, Frank Joyce, a University of California biologist and expert on the rain forest. ''And Frank says, 'Well, this is where they hang out.' ''    \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 ''They'' were aggressive and deadly snakes. ''Sure enough, we round this bend and this fer-de-lance is rattling away at us,'' recalled Mr. Newmark, the chief organizer of the hike and co-chief executive of the organic vitamin and supplement maker New Chapter. ''It was about as thick as Albert Pujols's baseball bat.''    \par \par \uc2 One hiker, Stephen Brooks of Kopali Organics, was attacked, but his boot kept the snake's fangs from digging into skin.    \par \par \uc2 The trouble did not stop there. The hike was so physically taxing -- 28 kilometers, or about 17 miles, up and down mountains -- that some older, or beefier, members of the entourage barely made it.    \par \par \uc2 There was even talk about trying to bring in horses or a helicopter to rescue the stragglers. That did not happen, but Mr. Newmark was ultimately hauled out of the jungle on a stretcher after injuring his knee.    \par \par \uc2 The trek, intentionally or not, served as a metaphor for the difficulty many of the executives are having as they transition from niche marketers to big-business men who have grown wealthy as demand for their products has surged. That is a good problem to have, of course, but it has stirred worries among them about selling out and has reaffirmed a desire to stay true to their cause.    \par \par \uc2 ''The whole landscape is shifting, and I think everyone is struggling to redefine their strategy in the midst of huge change that ain't finished,'' said Jeffrey Hollender, the president of Seventh Generation, which makes nontoxic household products like cleaners and diapers. ''It's still sort of in the early stages.''    \par \par \uc2 The hike was organized, in part, to help raise $10 million to expand a swath of preserved forest in the northwest part of the country that includes the Monteverde Cloud Forest Reserve and the Children's Eternal Rain Forest. Among those on the trip on Feb. 5 and 6 were Walter Robb, co-president of Whole Foods; Anthony Zolezzi, a founder of Pet Promise, a natural pet food company; and Bryan Meehan, the founder of   \uc2 Fresh & Wild\uc2  Stores in Britain, who is now chief executive of Nude Skincare. They are, Mr. Newmark said, ''the true spiritual warriors and visionaries of our industry.''    \par \par \uc2 They also invited a reporter and a photographer from The New York Times (whose expenses were paid by The Times). They joined the eight green business leaders as well as Professor Joyce and his wife, Katie; and a collection of local guides and conservationists.    \par \par \uc2 Mr. Newmark said the idea for the hike came to him last summer when he invited Michael Besancon, who oversees the environmental task force at Whole Foods, to visit his company's spice farm and lodge nearby. ''I really had no idea how daunting a task it was going to be,'' Mr. Newmark said.    \par \par \uc2 The hike began in the remote mountain town of Monteverde on a sunny and crisp morning. We shoved sandwiches in our backpacks, grabbed walking sticks and set off through the cloud forest that runs along the tops of mountain ridges. On a wooden platform above the tree line that straddled the Continental Divide, Mr. Newmark pointed out the corridor of land running to the Pacific Ocean that conservationists hope to buy and turn back into a rain forest.    \par \par \uc2 The preservationists are also planning to raise money at a fund-raiser in Hollywood in May and have just released a children's book, ''The Forever Forest: Kids Save a Tropical Treasure.''    \par \par \uc2 As the hike continued through the morning and became more grueling, the hikers splintered into groups and the talk turned to the state of the natural products industry.    \par \par \uc2 A recurring theme was authenticity, and how to maintain it as big companies try to burnish their green credentials.    \par \par \uc2 Some of the hikers also scoffed at the notion of companies and consumers buying carbon offsets, as a sign of their concern about the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , without making any real effort to reduce their carbon footprints. Mr. Zolezzi, who sold Pet Promise to   \uc2 Nestle\uc2  Purina Pet Care in 2004, argued that such offsets allow people to buy a few trees so they can drive their sport utility vehicles without guilt.    \par \par \uc2 His opinion was seconded by Mr. Meehan, who sold his   \uc2 Fresh & Wild\uc2  grocery stores to Whole Foods in 2004. ''I call it the ethical pat on the back,'' he said.    \par \par \uc2 Mr. Hollender of Seventh Generation said he believed that some of the founding principles of the organic and natural movement could be diluted as larger companies bought up those companies or started competing brands.    \par \par \uc2 He also maintained that some companies have started \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  departments even as they pursue goals that directly contradict them.    \par \par \uc2 Seventh Generation, the maker of nontoxic household products, is facing its own quandary. The company made its name at   \uc2 Whole Foods Market\uc2 , but with a flood of new competitors, including a line of natural cleaners from Clorox, Seventh Generation is now debating whether to sell its products at   \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2 , a company once reviled by environmentalists that has now embraced green products and sustainability programs.    \par \par \uc2 ''We are viewed in some respects, and it's not entirely fair, as this pure and virginal idea of what a business can be,'' Mr. Hollender said. ''And a lot of people believe we would taint ourselves by doing business at   \uc2 Wal-Mart.\uc2 ''    \par \par \uc2 Whole Foods, meanwhile, is striving to remain unique as the small upstart brands that have come to define the store are being lured by buyout offers and bigger grocery chains. Mr. Robb said he was so frustrated with companies making their names at Whole Foods and then cashing out that the company is changing its procurement practices.    \par \par \uc2 While selling to   \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  may be a natural evolution for Seventh Generation, it creates problems for Whole Foods, which does not want to compete on price with discount retailers.    \par \par \uc2 ''We are just not going to be taken for granted,'' Mr. Robb said, adding that the company may drop brands that have ''migrated in not a sustainable direction.'' The chain, he said, is ''going to look for people who want to partner primarily with Whole Foods.''    \par \par \uc2 For all the money flowing into the natural products industry, the overnight lodging on the hike was a stark reminder of its humble roots. The hikers stayed at a one-time farmhouse now overgrown and used as a jungle bunkhouse; among the accommodations were two toilets, two cold showers and two rooms outfitted with metal bunks and thin, mangy mattresses. A palm-size spider shared one of the showers, and a rat kept residence in the kitchen as we devoured rice and beans for dinner.    \par \par \uc2 On the advice of the locals, we slept in mosquito nets pulled tight under the mattress to keep out mosquitoes and the vinchuca bug, which emerges at night to burrow in sleepers' lips, causing a potentially deadly illness. But it was not the bugs that kept the group awake; it was the snoring. A handful of hikers created a thunderous racket, so loud in fact that Mr. Robb finally yelled at his Whole Foods' colleague Mr. Besancon to stop.    \par \par \uc2 ''That's an order,'' Mr. Meehan added.    \par \par \uc2 The second day of hiking was shorter but no less difficult, because of blisters and one painful case of chafing.    \par \par \uc2 There was also Mr. Newmark's left knee, which kept him on the trail well after dark. He finally refused to go any farther while climbing down a hill known as La Mona, a name he said in an e-mail message later, that also described the feeling in his knee. ''It gave and gave but finally gave out.''    \par \par \uc2 He arrived at the lodge at 11 p.m., having been carried on a stretcher for the last three kilometers by local guides.    \par \par \uc2 For all the unpleasant surprises on the trail, Mr. Newmark retained a Zen-like calm befitting a former instructor of transcendental meditation, and he proclaimed the hike a success. No one died, the mosquito nets kept the vinchuca bug at bay, and the participants had contributed $190,000 toward preserving more of the rain forest.    \par \par \uc2 ''It was altogether too close of a brush with mortality,'' Mr. Newmark said. ''I can guarantee that raising that $10 million will be easy compared to that hike.''    \par \par \uc2 PHOTOS: Crossing a shaky bridge, top, and putting up a mosquito net, above, were part of a business hiking trip in the Costa Rican rain forest. (PHOTOGRAPHS BY JOHN LOOMIS FOR THE NEW YORK TIMES) (pg. C1); Bosque Eterno de Los Ninos, or Children's Eternal Rain Forest, in Costa Rica; Members of the hiking group included, from left, Anthony Zolezzi, Bryan Meehan, Stephen Brooks andWalter Robb. (PHOTOGRAPHS BY JOHN LOOMIS FOR THE NEW YORK TIMES) (pg. C4)    \par \par \uc2 MAP: A swath of forest in Costa Rica was the site of a hike. (pg. C4) Map showing Monteverde, Costa Rica.    \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gcat : \uc2 Political/General News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 usa : \uc2 United States | namz : \uc2 North America\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PUB\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 New York Times Digital (Full Text)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15