casters and other companies to show more social responsibility or face greater regulation under a Conservative government. \par \par \uc2 The Tory leader's renewed attack on corporate behaviour is part of his attempt to rebrand his party as being on the side of the consumer, but it could cause irritation in some boardrooms. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Launching a Conservative working group report on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Mr Cameron will say the Tories should be "not just the party of business but of responsible business". \par \par \uc2 Mr Cameron told the BBC yesterday he wanted -business to raise its own standards but that he stood ready to intervene where necessary. \par \par \uc2 "What you should be doing as a government is trying to get business to face up to its responsibilities and behave responsibly, and if that doesn't work then there is always the threat of regulation and legislation at the end of it,'' he said. "But . . . it's much stronger if you try to get business to accept their responsibilities." \par \par \uc2 Mr Cameron highlighted the fact many supermarkets forced parents to run a -"chocolate gauntlet" as they waited to pay at checkouts, with confectionery located within easy reach of children. \par \par \uc2 He said politicians had a duty to speak out, citing his own criticism of retailers who offered discounted chocolate at the checkout. \par \par \uc2 He also criticised the broadcasting of television programmes or advertisements inappropriate for young children before the watershed. \par \par \uc2 Mr Cameron's party is sending mixed messages about its relationship with corporate Britain, which started with the Tory leader's assertion he would "stand up to big business". \par \par \uc2 The Tories also seek to exploit the government's rocky relations with business - resulting from capital gains tax reforms and the non-domiciles crackdown - by promoting their own corporate credentials. \par \par \uc2 Their corporate responsibility strategy is based largely on a voluntary approach: today's report proposes a central mechanism of "responsibility deals" to encourage action on problems such as waste, obesity and binge drinking. \par \par \uc2 Those deals would be brokered by a Conservative government with industry figures. Companies signing up could be offered a lighter regulatory regime. Those that refused could be punished by bad publicity. \par \par \uc2 Mr Cameron is expected to announce that Archie Norman, former Tory MP and chief executive and chairman of Asda, will develop a strategy to extend waste agreements, which currently cover only a small proportion of products. \par \par \uc2 Peter Ainsworth, shadow \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  secretary, said: "We throw too much away, wasting precious natural resources as well as money. \par \par \uc2 "A responsibility deal on waste would aim to engage the skills and knowledge of businesses, consumers and the public sector in finding creative, effective and non-bureaucratic ways to make Britain greener and better off."  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard